1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. dxc5 Bxc5 {This natural recapture
is not the best. It took a while for black to realize that the queen capture
is much more flexible.} 6. Ngf3 Nf6 7. Bc4 Qc6 {White plays Qe2 to all of the
black's queen moves. He can later choose between Ne4, Nf1 or Nb3 for example:}
(7... Qh5 $5 {this was played by Tiviakov and Granda} 8. Qe2 O-O (8... Nc6 {
is possible but the knight is a bit misplaced on c6 I would recommend} 9. Ne4
Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Qg6 11. Qe2 $1 $14) 9. Nf1 $5 {with the obvious idea of Ng3} Bd6
10. Bg5 Nd5 $1 (10... h6 $6 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. O-O-O Bc7 {was seen in Alsina
Leal, D (2517)-Granda Zuniga, J (2688) Atarrabia ESP 2016 and now} 13. g4 $1 {
would have given white an overwhelming advantage}) 11. Ng3 Bxg3 (11... Qg6 12.
O-O-O) 12. fxg3 Nc6 {Kantans,T (2514)-Tiviakov,S (2608) Reykjavik ISL 2015 and
now} 13. Bd2 $1 $146 {with a slight advantage}) (7... Qd8 8. Qe2 Nc6 $6 {
as mentioned before the knight is not that great here} ({Better is} 8... O-O 9.
O-O Nbd7 $1 {with a more or less equal game} 10. Nb3 $5 (10. Re1 $5) (10. c3 $5
) 10... Bd6 (10... Qc7 $6 11. Nxc5 Nxc5 12. Ne5 $1 $14 {Yu,Y (2675)-Batchuluun,
T (2517) Incheon 2013}) 11. Nbd4 Re8 $1 {these positions are considered equal
but there is plenty of play ahead}) 9. Ne4 Nd4 $6 {this attempt to simplify
the position does not work} 10. Nxd4 Nxe4 (10... Bxd4 11. c3 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Bf6
13. Bb5+ {leaves the black king stuck in the center}) 11. Bb5+ $1 Kf8 {Adams,M
(2731)-Vega Holm,F (2404) Cala Galdana 2001} 12. c3 $1 $146 {would have
avoided Qxd4 with a tempo} Bxd4 13. Qxe4 Bf6 14. Be3 $14) (7... Qd6 8. Qe2 Qc7
(8... Nbd7 9. Nb3 {is not much different from the main line 7...Qc6}) 9. Ne4
Be7 10. Nxf6+ $5 (10. O-O {nothing wrong with this move either}) 10... Bxf6 11.
O-O O-O 12. Bd3 Nd7 13. c3 Nc5 {it seems white is forced to surrender the
bishop but he finds a way to keep pieces on the board} 14. Bg5 $5 Bxg5 (14...
Qd8 $1 15. Bxf6 Qxd3 16. Qe5 Nd7 17. Qd4 Qg6 18. Be5 f6 {followed by e5 could
have equalized}) 15. Nxg5 h6 (15... Nxd3 16. Qxd3 g6 17. Rad1 $14 {leaves
white with the open D file and some kingside weakness to exploit. Probably
nothing too serious though black must play accurate}) 16. Bh7+ Kh8 17. Bc2 b6
18. Rfd1 Bb7 19. Nf3 Bxf3 (19... Rfd8 20. Ne5 Kg8 $11) 20. Qxf3 $14 {Adams,M 
(2754)-Istratescu,A (2670) London 2013}) 8. Qe2 Nbd7 {Developing and at the
same time defending against the obvious threat of Bb5. Black could also play 8.
..a6} (8... a6 9. Nb3 Bd6 10. Bg5 $1 {I like this move} Nbd7 11. Nbd4 (11.
O-O-O $5 $14 {is an interesting novelty here}) 11... Qc7 $2 (11... Qe4 $1 {
was the only move} 12. O-O b5 13. Bd3 Qxe2 14. Bxe2 Bb7 15. a4 b4 {and black
should be OK}) 12. Nxe6 {the game is over} fxe6 13. Qxe6+ Be7 (13... Kd8 14.
O-O-O Bf4+ 15. Kb1 {White has a winning position}) 14. Qf7+ Kd8 15. O-O-O Rf8
16. Nd4 Rxf7 17. Ne6+ Ke8 18. Nxc7+ Kf8 19. Bxf7 Ra7 20. Be6 b5 21. Nd5 Nb6 22.
Bxf6 Bxf6 23. Bxc8 {1-0 (23) Adams,M (2740)-Wan,Y (2512) Tromsoe 2013}) 9. O-O
({it is better to start with} 9. Nb3 {and now if} Bd6 10. Nbd4 {gives black
some problems on b5 / e6} Qe4 {is bad because} 11. Be3 {followed by queenside
castle}) 9... O-O 10. Nb3 b6 {The main line} (10... Bd6 $5 11. Nbd4 Qc5 12. Be3
Qh5 {black's position is quite solid}) 11. Nxc5 {It is tempting to win the
bishop pair immediately but this is not the only way to do it} (11. Nfd4 $5 {
deserves attention too} Bxd4 (11... Qc7 12. Nxc5 Nxc5 13. b3) 12. Nxd4 Qc5 13.
c3 Bb7 14. Re1 Rac8 15. Bb3 {it's hard not to like white's position here})
11... Qxc5 12. b3 $1 $14 {this was Adam's novelty and gives white an easier
position to play. Although black is not without resources I'd take white any
day} Bb7 13. Bb2 Rfd8 (13... Qh5 $6 {allowed Adams to exhibit a free lesson on
how to convert a queenside majority + bishop pair advantage} 14. Ne5 $1 Qxe2
15. Bxe2 Nxe5 16. Bxe5 {with a technically won endgame} Rac8 17. c4 $1 Rfd8 18.
Rfd1 Kf8 19. f3 Ke7 20. Kf2 Ne8 21. a4 Rxd1 22. Rxd1 Rd8 23. Bd4 Bc6 24. a5 Rb8
25. b4 f6 26. b5 Bd7 27. c5 {1-0 (27) Adams,M (2704)-Martinovic,S (2509)
Rijeka 2010}) 14. Rfd1 Nf8 15. Ne5 Ng6 16. Nxg6 {We can stop here analyzing
the opening phase. It's a quite endgame for white in which he is playing for
two results.} (16. Rxd8+ Rxd8 17. Nxg6 hxg6 18. Rd1 $14) 16... hxg6 17. Qe5
Qxe5 18. Bxe5 Nd5 19. Rd2 f6 (19... Nb4 $5) 20. Bd4 Kf7 21. a4 Nb4 22. Rad1 $14
Bd5 23. Bc3 Nxc2 24. Ba6 Rdc8 25. Bxc8 Rxc8 26. Rxc2 Bxb3 27. Rd7+ Ke8 28. Rcd2
Bd5 29. Rxa7 Rxc3 30. h4 $18 {Although white is winning there are some
practical difficulties.} Kf8 31. Rd4 (31. Rb2 Kg8 32. Rxb6 $18) 31... Kg8 32.
Rb4 Kh7 33. f3 (33. Rxb6 Rc4 34. Rb1 $1 Rxh4 35. Ra1 Rg4 36. g3 {should give
white a win}) 33... Rc2 34. Ra6 (34. Rxb6) 34... Kh6 35. Raxb6 g5 36. Rd6 f5
37. Rd4 g6 38. hxg5+ Kxg5 39. a5 Ra2 40. a6 Kh5 41. Kf1 g5 42. Ke1 f4 43. Rd2
Ra1+ 44. Rd1 Ra2 45. Rd2 Ra1+ 46. Kf2 Bc4 47. g4+ fxg3+ 48. Kxg3 Rxa6 49. Rd8
Kg6 50. Rg8+ Kf6 51. Rd7 Bd5 52. Rf8+ Kg6 53. Rdf7 e5 54. Rf5 Re6 55. Kg4 Kg7
56. R8f7+ Kg6 57. Rd7 Bc6 58. Rxg5+ Kf6 59. Rf5+ Kg6 60. Rg5+ Kf6 61. Rf5+ Kg6
62. Rd3 e4 63. Re3 Bd7 64. Rg5+ Kf6 65. f4 Re5+ 66. Kh4 Re8 67. Kg3 Bf5 68. Ra3
Re6 69. Kf2 Rd6 70. Ra5 Bg6 71. Rgb5 Bh7 72. f5 Kg5 73. Ke3 Rf6 74. Kxe4 Rxf5
75. Rxf5+ Kg4 76. Ke5 Bxf5 77. Ra4+ Kg5 78. Ra1 Bc2 79. Re1 Bd3 80. Rg1+ Kh6
81. Kf6 Kh7 82. Rg3 Bb1 83. Rh3+ Kg8 84. Rh2 Bh7 {1/2-1/2 (84) Adams,M (2723)
-Lemos,D (2553) Caleta 2011} *

