1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. dxc5 Qxc5 {This move is more
flexible than 5...Bxc5 and allows black to play a quick Nd7-Nc5 chasing
white's bishop. This is the latest trend for black nowadays} 6. Ngf3 Nf6 7. Bd3
{there is no point in playing 7.Bc4 if there is no tempo to gain} Be7 (7...
Nbd7 {with the idea of Qc7 and quickly Nc5, most likely it will transpose
sooner or later after} 8. O-O Qc7 9. Nb3 Be7 10. a4 (10. Bg5 $5) (10. Re1)) 8.
O-O Nbd7 9. a4 $5 {This is the latest try, white attempts to create some
weakness on the queenside. White has alternatives but they are not much
different from the main line. They all lead to the same type of positions, for
example:} (9. Re1 $5 b6 (9... Qc7 10. Nd4 $5 O-O (10... Nc5 11. Bb5+ Bd7 12.
Bf1 {with the idea later of Nc4-e5}) 11. Nc4 b6 12. Nb5 Qc6 13. Ncd6 Ba6 14.
Bf4 Nc5 15. Nd4 Qd7 16. Bxa6 Nxa6 17. Nc4 Rac8 18. Ne5 Qd5 $2 (18... Qb7 $1 19.
Qe2 Nc5 $11) 19. Ndc6 Rfe8 20. Qe2 $16 {Agdestein,S (2625) -Narciso Dublan,M 
(2533) Llucmajor ESP 2014 Black can't cope with the threat of c4 and loses
material}) 10. Ne4 Qc7 11. Nxf6+ Bxf6 12. Ng5 Nc5 13. Bb5+ Bd7 14. Bxd7+ Qxd7
15. Qxd7+ Nxd7 16. Ne4 Be7 17. Bf4 {Naiditsch,A (2705)-Zhao Jun (2603) Danzhou
CHN 2014 Objectively this is an equal endgame. The best move for black now is:}
e5 18. Bg3 f6 19. Rad1 Rd8 {with idea of Kf7-Ke6 white has no advantage at all}
) (9. Qe2 $5 Qc7 10. Ne4 O-O 11. g3 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 g6 (12... Nf6 {is probably
better} 13. Qh4 Rd8 {black has very little to worry about here}) 13. Qe2 b6 14.
Bf4 Bd6 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Rfd1 Qc7 17. Bb5 Rd8 18. Ng5 Rb8 19. Nxe6 fxe6 20.
Qxe6+ Kh8 21. Rd2 a6 22. Bc6 b5 23. Rad1 Rb6 24. Rxd7 {1-0 (24) Rublevsky,S 
(2688)-Zhou,J (2668) Ningbo 2010}) 9... b6 (9... Qc7 $1 10. Nb3 (10. a5 Nc5 {
is the idea, now} 11. Bc4 O-O 12. Qe2 Rd8 13. Ne5 Bd6 14. Ndf3 Nce4 15. Bf4 $6
(15. Rd1 {is better} Bd7 16. Nxd7 Rxd7 17. g3 Rc8 18. Bd3 Nc5 19. Bb5 Rdd8 20.
Be3 h6 $11) 15... g5 $1 16. Bd3 gxf4 17. Bxe4 Nxe4 18. Qxe4 Bxe5 19. Nxe5 f6
20. Nf3 e5 $15 {Movsesian,S (2671) -Erdos,V (2624) Hersonissos GRE 2017}) 10...
O-O (10... b6 $1 {I believe this move is very important for black in order to
keep the balance.} 11. a5 (11. c3 Bb7) 11... Bb7 12. axb6 (12. a6 $5 Bd5 13.
Nbd4 Rc8 14. Bg5 {with the idea of Bh4-g3} O-O 15. Nb5 Qb8 16. Bh4 Qa8 $1 17.
Re1 Nc5 18. Bf1 Rfd8 19. c3 Nce4 20. Qc2 {followed by Rad1 The position is
roughly equal}) 12... axb6 13. Rxa8+ Bxa8 14. Qe2 O-O {Rogic,D (2581)-Palac,M 
(2583) Stari Mikanovci 2011} 15. Nbd4 $1 {with equality}) 11. a5 Ne5 (11... a6
12. Qe2 (12. Re1) (12. c3 {are also two standard moves in this type of
positions}) 12... Re8 13. Bg5 Nd5 14. Bxe7 Rxe7 15. Rfd1 Nf4 16. Qe3 Nxd3 17.
Qxd3 Nf8 18. Qd6 Qxd6 19. Rxd6 Rc7 20. c3 f6 21. Nfd2 e5 {Another endgame with
equal chances in which black goes wrong quickly} 22. Ra4 Kf7 (22... Be6 $1 23.
Rb4 Re8 {keeps the balance}) 23. Rc4 Rxc4 (23... Rd7 24. Rxd7+ Bxd7 25. Rc7 Rb8
26. Nc5 Rc8 $1 27. Rxc8 Bxc8 {and black holds}) 24. Nxc4 $14 Ke7 25. Rb6 Nd7
26. Rb4 Rb8 27. Nb6 Nxb6 28. Rxb6 $16 {White has a clear advantage due to his
queenside pressure and better pieces. He went on to win Robson,R (2670)
-Chandra,A (2490) Saint Louis USA 2016}) (11... Nc5 $5 12. Nxc5 Qxc5 13. Be3
Qc7 14. Bd4 Rd8 15. Be5 (15. Re1 $5) 15... Qc5 (15... Bd6 $1) 16. Qe2 Bd7 {
Fressinet,L (2660)-Vocaturo,D (2606) Caleta ENG 2017} 17. c3 $5 $14) 12. Nxe5
Qxe5 13. Re1 Qc7 14. Bg5 (14. Qe2 $5 Bd7 15. a6 b6 16. Nd4 $5) 14... Bd7 15.
Nd4 (15. Bh4 $5) 15... Rad8 16. Qf3 Nd5 17. Bxe7 Nxe7 18. Qg3 Qxg3 19. hxg3 Nc6
20. Nxc6 Bxc6 21. Re5 {½-½ (21) Adams,M (2745)-Nisipeanu,L (2687) Baden
Baden GER 2016 There is no great story in this game by M. Adams but white has
room for improvements}) 10. a5 b5 $2 (10... bxa5 11. Nb3 Qc7 12. Nxa5 {is not
much but it is more than white gets in the usual lines. Still, it had to be
tried}) 11. Nb3 (11. Ne4 {is also strong}) 11... Qh5 $2 (11... Qc7 12. Bxb5 a6
13. Bd3 Bb7 {could be playable, black does have a bit of compensation for the
pawn. The move played in the game just doesn't stand}) 12. a6 $16 b4 13. Be2 $1
Nb6 (13... Qd5 14. Nfd4 {with Bf3 coming}) 14. Ra5 Nbd5 15. Ng5 (15. Re1 {
threatening Ne5 would have been winning too}) 15... Qg6 16. Bd3 Qh5 17. Bb5+
Kf8 18. Qxh5 Nxh5 19. Bc6 Rb8 20. Bxd5 $18 exd5 21. Be3 Ra8 22. Nd4 (22. Nf3
Nf6 23. Ne5 $18) 22... Bd8 23. Rxd5 Bb6 24. Ne4 f5 25. Nxf5 Bxa6 26. Rfd1 g6
27. Bh6+ Kf7 28. Ng5+ Kf6 29. Rd6+ Kxf5 30. R1d5+ Kg4 31. h3+ Kf4 32. Nf3+ {
and mate in two moves 1-0 (32) Adams,M (2751)-Ju Wenjun (2583) Caleta ENG 2017}
*

