1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 Qe7+ {This move
has come into fashion lately and it should be taken seriously.} 7. Be2 (7. Qe2
{is the alternative but it's too early to go into the endgame, at least for me
so my repertoire choice is 7.Be2}) 7... Qc7 {This is the main line but let's
have a look at 7...cxd4 A Korchnoi's favorite} (7... cxd4 8. O-O Qc7 9. Nb3 Nf6
10. Nbxd4 Be7 {white's advantage here is tiny. There is nothing conclusive or
a forced way to put black under great pressure.} (10... a6 {is the move
Korchnoi employed twice with great success against Grandmasters Alexander
Lastin and Sergey Rublevsky} 11. Nxc6 $1 {this has only been played once
according to my database but I think it's the way to go} (11. Re1 Be7 12. Bg5
O-O 13. c3 {is a slightly better for white too}) 11... bxc6 12. c4 $1 Bd6 (
12... Be7 {is better but does not change much} 13. Qc2 O-O 14. cxd5 Nxd5 15.
Bd2 {looks better for white}) 13. Bg5 Ne4 14. Be3 Be6 15. Rc1 O-O 16. cxd5 Bxd5
17. Bc4 Qa5 18. Qc2 Nf6 19. Bxd5 cxd5 {Nikolaidis,I (2561)-Skaperdas,K (2200)
Nikaia GRE 2017} 20. Qc6 $1 $14) 11. Nb5 Qd8 12. c3 O-O 13. Qc2 Bg4 14. Be3 Qc8
(14... Qd7 15. Rad1) 15. Rad1 Bf5 16. Qc1 Rd8 17. Rfe1 Be4 18. Nd2 a6 $6 ({
Black should just play} 18... Bg6 19. Nb3 a6 20. N5d4 {and the game goes on.
White's edge is minimal}) 19. Nxe4 $1 Nxe4 20. Nd4 $16 {Grandelius,N (2635)
-Sundararajan, K (2508) Caleta ENG 2016 Besides having the better pawn
structure now white also has the bishop pair, I think white is clearly better.}
) 8. dxc5 $1 {A direct approach going straight to play against the IQP
structure. White can also keep the tension for a little longer. Let's see the
alternative} (8. O-O Nf6 9. Re1 {if black moves the bishop from f8 then white
is happy to capture on c5 as black will lose another tempo. Therefore black
can make the useful move Be6 or he can even take on d4 since there is no
winning discover check for white.} Be6 (9... cxd4 10. Nb3 Bb4 11. Bd2 Bxd2 12.
Qxd2 O-O 13. Nfxd4 Bd7 14. Nxc6 bxc6 (14... Bxc6 15. Bf3 Rfe8 16. Qd4 a6 17. c3
Re7 18. Rxe7 Qxe7 {was better for white in Kotronias,V (2580)-Zvjaginsev,V 
(2655) Legnica 2013 Black even managed to win this game but i'm sure Kotronias
would take this position again with white anytime. One possible improvement
would be bringing the knight from b3 to e3 for example with Nd2-Nf1.}) 15. Nc5
Bf5 16. Bf3 (16. Bd3 $5) 16... Rfe8 17. h3 (17. c3 Bg4 $1 {is a bit annoying})
17... h6 (17... Qd6 $5 18. b4 Rxe1+ 19. Rxe1 a5 20. a3 axb4 21. axb4 Nd7 {
Black equalizes here}) 18. c3 Be4 19. Bxe4 Nxe4 20. Nxe4 dxe4 21. Rad1 Qa5 22.
b4 Qa4 23. Qd4 a5 24. Rd2 axb4 25. cxb4 Rab8 26. Rxe4 Rxe4 27. Qxe4 c5 28. g3 {
1/2-1/2 (28) Rublevsky,S (2702)-Zvjaginsev,V (2660) Berlin GER 2015}) (9... Be7
{is playable too} 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Nb3 Be7 12. h3 h6 13. Bd3 O-O 14. c3 Re8 {
Gonzalez Vidal,Y (2543)-Harikrishna,P (2743) Tbilisi GEO 2017} 15. Be3 $14 {
with the following plan Qc2-Nbd4-Rad1}) 10. Bb5 Bd6 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Nb3 Bb6
13. Be3 O-O 14. h3 Rfe8 15. c3 Ne4 16. Nfd4 $14 {Bauer,C (2602)-Tereick,B 
(2378) Zuerich 2009 I'm not sure of black's 15...Ne4}) 8... Bxc5 9. Nb3 Bb6 (
9... Be7 10. c3 (10. Qxd5 $4 Nb4 $19) 10... Nf6 11. O-O O-O 12. Bg5 $14 {
typical IQP position for white. The plan Re1-Bh4-g3 Nfd4 etc.}) 10. O-O Be6 (
10... Nf6 {is possible. White can attempt to 'punish' with} 11. Bg5 Qd6 (11...
Be6 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Qd2 $14) 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Qxd5 Qxb2 14. Qe4+ Kf8 (14...
Be6 15. Ba6 $1 $16 {a shocker} Nd8 16. Bb5+ Kf8 17. a4 $16) 15. a4 $14) 11.
Nfd4 Nf6 12. Nxe6 $5 {The position arising after this move is about equal but
I'm pretty sure that to the human eye is quite simple to understand why Adams
played it. White take's the bishop pair, tries to open the position and he
still keeps a slightly better pawn structure. What can go wrong?} (12. c4 $5
$146 {is an interesting novelty} Nxd4 13. Nxd4 O-O 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. cxd5 Ne4
16. Be3 {only move} Bxe3 17. fxe3 Rxf1+ 18. Qxf1 (18. Bxf1 Qf7 $1 19. Qc2 exd5
$11) 18... Qb6 19. Qc1 exd5 $11) (12. Be3 O-O 13. c3 {is the standard way of
playing}) 12... fxe6 13. c4 dxc4 $6 (13... O-O 14. c5 $14) (13... Qf7 $5 {
could be a major improvement for black here} 14. cxd5 exd5 15. a4 a6 $1 16. Bg5
O-O 17. Rc1 Ne4 18. Be3 {sad move to play but white can't stand the bishop on
b6 any longer} Bxe3 19. fxe3 Qe6 20. Bf3 {the game is roughly even}) 14. Bxc4
O-O 15. Qe2 Kh8 16. Be3 $14 {White has a slight edge but there is a lot to do
still. The rest of the game is a delight to see} Bxe3 17. Qxe3 Nd5 18. Qe4 Nf4
19. Rac1 Qe5 20. Qxe5 Nxe5 21. Rfd1 Nxc4 22. Rxc4 Rad8 23. Rxd8 Rxd8 24. h4 e5
25. g3 Nd3 26. Rc2 b6 27. Kf1 Nb4 28. Rc7 a5 29. a3 Nd3 30. Rc2 Rf8 31. Nc1 Nc5
32. Ke2 h6 33. Nd3 Nxd3 34. Kxd3 Rf3+ 35. Kc4 e4 36. Re2 Kh7 37. Kd5 Rb3 38.
Kxe4 Kg6 39. Ke5 Kf7 40. g4 Rb5+ 41. Kd6 Rb3 42. Kc6 Kf6 43. f3 a4 44. Re4 Rxb2
45. Rxa4 Rb3 46. Rf4+ Kg6 47. a4 Kh7 48. Kb7 Kg8 49. Rd4 Kf7 50. Rc4 Rb2 51. f4
Rb3 52. f5 Rb2 53. g5 hxg5 54. hxg5 Rb3 55. Ka6 Rb2 56. g6+ Kf6 57. Rc6+ Kxf5
58. Rxb6 Ra2 59. a5 Ke5 60. Kb5 Ra1 61. a6 Kd5 62. Rb7 {1-0 (62) Adams,M (2727)
-Nikolaidis,I (2519) Hersonissos GRE 2017} *

