1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 Bd6 7. O-O Nge7 (
7... Nf6 {is a mistake} 8. Re1+ Be6 9. Nb3 $1 c4 10. Nc5 {black is forced to
surrender his good bishop and his position looks bad}) 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Nb3 Bb6
{The problem with this move is that white gets to trade the dark squares
bishop rather easily and secure control of the d4 square. Again, I must say
that it is very difficult to prove a clear edge for white in many of these
lines but the better structure counts. In many games I have analyzed while the
engines at some point gave 0.00 the player with white often manages to win
anyway, which led me to the conclusion that white's position is simply easier
to play.} (9... Bd6 {is considered the main line}) 10. Re1 O-O 11. Be3 Bg4 (
11... Bxe3 12. Rxe3 Bg4 {was played by the great Viktor Korchnoi who defended
this line more than once, succesfully} 13. h3 Bh5 (13... Bxf3 14. Qxf3 $14) 14.
c3 $5 Nf5 (14... Qb6 15. Bxc6) (14... Qc7 15. Be2 Rad8 16. Nfd4 Bg6 17. Bf3 Ne5
18. Qe2 N7c6 19. Nxc6 Nxf3+ 20. Qxf3 bxc6 {Kotronias,V (2599)-Thamtavatvorn,T 
(2214) Mallorca 2004} 21. Nc5 $14) 15. Re1 Nh4 16. Be2 Re8 17. Nxh4 (17. Nfd4
Qg5 $1) 17... Bxe2 18. Rxe2 Qxh4 19. Rxe8+ Rxe8 20. Qxd5 $1 (20. Qd2 $11 {
The position is equal, although eventually white won in Quesada Perez, Y (2452)
-Otero Acosta,D (2527) Merida 2013}) 20... Re2 21. Qf3 $1 Rxb2 22. Re1 $1 {
would have given white a dangerous initiative} g6 23. Re8+ Kg7 24. Nc5 Nd8 25.
Qe3 Rb6 26. g4 {with a winning attack}) (11... Bf5 $5 12. c3 (12. Bxb6 Qxb6 13.
Bd3 Rad8 14. Bxf5 Nxf5 15. Qd2 d4 16. Ne5 Qc7 17. Nxc6 Qxc6 18. Qd3 g6 19. Re2
Rfe8 20. Rae1 Rxe2 21. Rxe2 h5 {was equal in Akopian,V (2648)-Sundararajan,K 
(2513) Doha QAT 2015 although Akopian managed to win}) 12... Be4 13. Nfd4 Re8
14. Ba4 $5 {this is a nice idea, the threat is Nc5!} Qc8 (14... Qd6 15. Nxc6
Nxc6 16. Bxb6 axb6 17. Bb5 $14) 15. Qd2 $14) 12. Bxb6 {If you don't like what
