1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 Bd6 7. O-O Nge7 8.
dxc5 Bxc5 9. Nb3 Bd6 {This is the main line and now we continue with} 10. Re1 {
Another move order worth of attention is} (10. h3 O-O 11. Bd3 $1 {White has
played h3 instead of Re1, both moves are part of white's development plan so
the variations could transpose into each other at some point. White scores
really well here. Let's see some examples of how the game can develop:} h6 (
11... Bf5 {is solid but also a bit passive, white is happy to trade pieces.
One possible continuation is} 12. Bxf5 Nxf5 13. Qd3 Qd7 14. Bd2 {with Rad1 next
}) 12. c3 (12. Re1 $5 {is likely to transpose to the main game.}) 12... Nf5 (
12... Bf5 {is better but white keeps the typical small edge after} 13. Bxf5
Nxf5 14. Re1 Qd7 15. Qd3 $14) 13. Bc2 $1 {Remember this idea, c3-Bc2-Qd3 not
only creates serious threats against the black king but also is a perfect
coordination for white's pieces} Be6 (13... Qf6 {an active move but black does
not get enough compensation for the pawn} 14. Qxd5 Be6 15. Qe4 Rfe8 16. Nbd4
Nfxd4 17. Nxd4 Nxd4 18. cxd4 (18. Qh7+ $5 Kf8 19. cxd4 Qxd4 $6 20. Re1 $16)
18... g6 19. Qd3 Rac8 20. Bb3 Bf5 21. Qf3 Qxd4 22. Bxh6 Qe5 23. g3 Qh8 24. Rad1
Be5 {Bruzon Batista, L (2694)-Rodriguez Vila, A (2518) Quito 2012 Bruzon has
been playing a perfect game so far and now} 25. Bg5 $1 Qxh3 26. Rfe1 Qg4 27.
Qxb7 Be6 28. Bxe6 Qxe6 29. Rd2 $16 {would have kept black under big pressure.})
(13... Bc7 14. Qd3 g6 {has been played a few times.} 15. Rd1 $5 Qf6 16. Qxd5
Rd8 17. Qe4 Rxd1+ 18. Bxd1 {black does not have enough for the pawn}) 14. Qd3
Qf6 15. g4 $1 g6 {creative play from Vaganian here but black's position is not
solid enough} 16. Re1 $1 (16. gxf5 $2 Bxf5) 16... Rfe8 (16... Rad8 17. Kg2 $16)
17. Rxe6 $1 fxe6 18. gxf5 gxf5 19. Bd2 Rad8 20. Kh1 $16 {white's advantage is
unquestionable Navara,D (2737)-Vaganian,R (2562) Biel SUI 2017}) 10... O-O 11.
Bd3 $1 {This move prevents Bg4 due to Bxh7+} h6 {This is the main move and the
alternatives don't seem to be much better, for example:} (11... Ng6 12. Bg5 Qd7
13. c3 Nf4 14. Bf1 Qf5 15. Bh4 Qh5 16. Bg3 Bg4 17. Qd2 $1 Qh6 (17... Bxf3 18.
Bxf4) 18. Nfd4 Qf6 19. h3 Be6 20. Nb5 $16 {white converted his advantage in
Akopian,V (2550)-Vladimirov,E (2565) Moscow 1990}) (11... Qc7 12. c3 Ng6 13. h3
$16 {and it is not clear what black is doing} Nge5 14. Bc2 Nxf3+ 15. Qxf3 Be6
16. Be3) (11... Nf5 12. c3 {is similar}) 12. h3 Nf5 13. c3 Qf6 {This is the
main move but black has an interesting alternative} (13... Bc7 $5 14. Bc2 Qd6
15. Qd3 g6 {and here I like} 16. Bd2 $5 {with idea of} Bd7 17. c4 $1 dxc4 18.
Qxc4 Be6 (18... Rfe8 19. Bxf5 Bxf5 20. Bxh6 Ne5 21. Nxe5 Rxe5 22. Qc3 $1 $16)
19. Qc3 Kh7 20. Bxf5 Bxf5 21. Rad1 Rfe8 22. Bxh6 Rxe1+ 23. Qxe1 Qf6 24. Bd2
Qxb2 $2 25. Bc3 $18 Qxa2 26. Nbd4 Rd8 27. Nxc6 bxc6 28. Rxd8 Bxd8 29. Qe8 {
1-0 (29) Mista,A (2609)-Tomczak,J (2547) Warsaw POL 2014}) 14. Bc2 Rd8 15. Qd3
g6 16. Qd2 (16. Bd2 $5 {deserves attention too and might be even stronger than
Adam's move in this game} a5 17. a4 b6 18. Qe2 Ba6 19. Qd1 $14 {Black has
issues with his pawn on h6} Kh7 20. Bxf5 $1 Qxf5 21. Nbd4 Nxd4 22. Nxd4 Qf6 23.
Be3 $14 Bc7 24. Qd2 g5 25. Nf3 Qf5 26. h4 gxh4 27. Nxh4 Qh5 {Rublevsky,S (2679)
-Lysyj,I (2578) Krasnoyarsk 2007} 28. Bf4 $1 $16) (16. Nh2 {is a direct
approach that forces black's next move} Bxh2+ (16... h5 {is bad because} 17.
Nf3 {the square g5 is now weak} Nh4 18. Nxh4 Qxh4 19. Bh6 {with idea of Rad1
white is better}) 17. Kxh2 d4 {the only decent try} (17... Nh4 $2 {worked
badly for the specialist Vaganian} 18. Bxh6 $1 Ne5 (18... Qxf2 19. Re2 $18) 19.
Qg3 Nef3+ 20. gxf3 Nxf3+ 21. Kg2 {1-0 (21) Khalifman,A (2624)-Vaganian,R (2590)
Bazna 2007}) 18. Bf4 b6 $1 (18... dxc3 19. Qxc3 Qxc3 20. bxc3 $14) 19. Nd2 Nd6
20. Qg3 dxc3 21. bxc3 {I like white's position here, he has two bishops and
the position is open} g5 22. Be3 Bf5 (22... Qxc3 {is critical but white has
some initiative} 23. Rac1 Qg7 24. f4 $1 Bf5 25. Bb3 $36 {this doesn't look
like the kind of position black would enter voluntarily.}) 23. Ba4 b5 24. Bb3
Bg6 25. f4 $1 Nf5 26. fxg5 Qe7 $2 (26... Qxc3 {was the only move to stay in
the game} 27. Rac1 Qxb3 28. Nxb3 Nxg3 29. Rxc6 Nf5 30. Bc1 hxg5 31. Bxg5 Rd6 {
with even chances}) 27. Qf2 hxg5 28. Bf4 {black loses material 1-0 (28)
Timofeev,A (2658)-Lysyj,I (2590) Sochi 2007}) 16... Bf8 17. Qf4 $1 {I like
this approach, it puts your opponent's preparation in question. See the next
note} (17. Qe2 {is also possible and was played by M. Adams two years later}
Nd6 $1 {the best move} (17... Bg7 18. Bxf5 Bxf5 19. Be3 $14 {the outpost on d4
outweighs the bishop pair in these type of IQP positions}) 18. Nbd4 Re8 19. Qf1
Rxe1 20. Qxe1 Bd7 21. Bb3 Nc4 22. Bxc4 dxc4 23. Be3 {Adams,M (2729)-Zugic, I 
(2477) Khanty-Mansiysk 2007} Re8 {keeps the balance}) (17. Nh2 {is the most
popular move in this position but I don't advise it because} a5 $1 {gives
black good play.}) 17... Bg7 {This has been played a lot} (17... Bd6 $1 18. Qa4
(18. Qd2 {Was the move actually played by M. Adams in his game against Zugic
and then he went 19.Qe2}) 18... Bf8 (18... Bd7 19. Bxf5 $1 {destroys black's
