1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Be7 $5 {I give the interesting mark to this move
because it is certainly one invitation for a complicated game. It has been
played by the main French specialists such as Morozevich, Korchnoi, Short,
Knaak among others. It's a useful move which asks white to play one more move
and define his intentions, meanwhile, Be7 can't do any harm for black.} 4. Ngf3
{We continue following Mickey Adams path} ({In my last game in this variation
I chose} 4. e5 {against Vocaturo and it worked out quite nicely for white in
that game but I've found a few improvements for black that put me off this
variation.}) 4... Nf6 {Other moves make little sense right now. Nevertheless,
let's have a look at a couple of alternatives} (4... b6 {black is dreaming
that white reacts with 5.e5 and then play c5-Ba6 with decent play. While this
structure is playable, white can try to tame black's hopes with} 5. exd5 exd5
6. Ne5 Bb7 7. Bb5+ c6 8. Qg4 g6 9. Bd3 Nf6 10. Qe2 $14 {this symmetrical
structure with more active pieces should favor white. Just look at the strong
knight on e5, the weak square h6 and passive bishop on b7. Definitely a
pleasant position for white} (10. Qh3)) (4... c5 {Okay so black claims that he
can benefit from white having played Ngf3? I find it hard to believe.} 5. exd5
{of course this is the natural reaction as seen in the lines with 3...c5} exd5
6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. Nb3 Bb6 8. Bb5+ Nc6 9. O-O Nge7 10. Re1 {white is a tempo up
compared to other lines}) 5. e5 Nfd7 6. c3 c5 7. Bd3 b6 $5 {This is our first
line, black wants to solve the problem of the c8 bishop with Ba6. The lines
after 7...Nc6 are analyzed in the next game} 8. O-O {This white's natural move
but here let me give you a worthy alternative:} (8. Nf1 $5 {is an interesting
way to continue. Since white can't do anything to prevent the trade of bishops
he might as well accelerate the play on the kingside. The idea is Ng3-Nh5} Ba6
9. Bxa6 $1 (9. Ng3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 {has been tried in a few games and white has
scored quite well, however, things are unclear as shown in the following games}
Qc8 $146 {Has never been tried and is the move that concerned me the most but
still white has decent chances, for example:} (10... Nc6 11. Bd2 Rc8 12. O-O $1
{is safer} (12. h4 $5 {typical approach on the kingside that not only takes
control over the square g5 and threatens h5-h6 but also enables ideas like Rh3.
} cxd4 13. cxd4 Nb4 14. Bxb4 Bxb4+ 15. Kd1 Be7 16. Rc1 h6 17. Nh5 O-O 18. Nf4
Rxc1+ 19. Kxc1 Qc7+ 20. Kb1 Rc8 21. g4 Qc4 {Black is totally fine here} 22. Qd2
$2 {Naiditsch, A (2724)-Jorczik, J (2405) Eppingen GER 2014 Black could have
taken the initiative with} (22. Qd1 Nc5 $1) 22... Nc5 $1 $17) 12... O-O 13. Nh5
Na5 14. Rad1 {to have Bc1 on Nc4} Re8 {Antipov,M (2581)-Hoang Thanh Trang 
(2463) Budapest HUN 2017} (14... Qc7 15. Bg5 $5) 15. h3 $5 {with the idea of
Nh2-Ng4 could be an interesting plan here}) 11. O-O Qa6 12. Qd2 O-O 13. Rd1 {
necessary to play this move before sending the queen the kingside} (13. Qf4 Qd3
) 13... Rc8 14. Qf4 cxd4 15. cxd4 Qc4 {black will play Qc2 when the time is
right and help on the kingside defense. The position is unclear}) 9... Nxa6 10.
Ng3 b5 (10... O-O {is probably better} 11. O-O Rc8 12. Qd3 Nab8 {is a
transposition to 9.0-0}) 11. O-O Nab8 12. a4 cxd4 (12... b4 13. cxb4 cxd4 (
13... cxb4 {is a position in which black does not have much counterplay on
queenside/center} 14. Nh5 O-O 15. Nd2 $5 {with idea of Qg4 looks good for
example}) 14. Nh5 O-O 15. Qxd4 {followed by a queen transfer to g4}) 13. axb5 (
13. cxd4 bxa4) 13... dxc3 14. bxc3 Qc7 15. Qd4 g6 ({better is} 15... O-O 16.
Be3 $13) 16. c4 $5 (16. Bh6 $16) 16... Qxc4 17. Qxc4 dxc4 18. Be3 Nc5 19. Nd4
O-O 20. Rfc1 Nd3 $6 21. Rxc4 $16 {Nisipeanu,L (2678)-Anton Guijarro,D (2628)
Baku AZE 2015}) 8... Ba6 9. Ne1 $5 {The knight starts its journey to f4 while
freeing the queen to go to g4} Bxd3 (9... O-O 10. Qg4 {leads to similar play}
Qc8 11. Ndf3 f5 12. Qg3 Nc6 13. Bg5 Rf7 14. h4 Nf8 15. h5 cxd4 16. cxd4 Bxg5
17. Qxg5 h6 18. Qd2 Rc7 19. Rc1 Qb7 20. b4 $1 $14 {Dvirnyy,D (2549)-Drasko,M 
(2462) Porto San Giorgio 2013}) 10. Nxd3 Nc6 11. Qg4 g6 (11... O-O 12. Nf3) (
11... g5 {is an interesting idea that forces white to play precise} 12. Qh5 $1
{unfortunately for black this move puts an end to his hopes of playing h5} cxd4
13. Nf3 dxc3 14. Nxg5 Bxg5 15. Bxg5 Qc7 16. Nf4 Nf8 {Alonso,S (2516)-Gaitan,J 
(2283) La Plata 2012} 17. bxc3 $16) 12. Nf3 h5 (12... c4 13. Nf4 Qc8 $5 {
this is an interesting plan, black wants Bd8 and Ne7 bringing the knight to
the precious square f5} 14. h4 h5 15. Qg3 Nf8 16. b3 $5 (16. b4 {white can
also try this move}) 16... b5 17. a4 a6 18. b4 Bd8 19. Nh3 Ne7 20. Bg5 Nh7 21.
Bxe7 Bxe7 {Navara,D (2730)-Demidov,M (2497) Czech Republic CZE 2015} 22. Rfb1
$14 {white is better. The plan is Ra2-Rba1 with pressure on both wings}) 13.
Qg3 c4 {This gives black a sense of safety although his problems aren't over.
With the dark squares, weak white will have permanent pressure on black's
kingside. In another game of Adams black decided to keep the tension with 13...
Qc7 but it didn't work out well} (13... Qc7 14. Bg5 $1 O-O-O 15. b4 c4 16. Nf4
Rde8 17. b5 (17. h4 {is already a good idea here}) 17... Nd8 18. Bxe7 Rxe7 19.
Rfe1 Ree8 20. Ng5 {white has more space and constant pressure on f7. Whether
or not black's position is defensible, clearly is not a position one would
enjoy. Adams,M (2735)-Paehtz,E (2459) England 2012}) 14. Nde1 h4 $6 {Lemos
tries to active his rook, or simply get the queen out of g4 but it only
improves white's position} (14... b5 $5 {is definitely a better try} 15. a3 Nb6
16. Nc2 a5 17. Bg5 $14) 15. Qg4 Rh5 16. h3 $1 b5 17. Nc2 Nb6 18. Qf4 Rf5 19.
Qe3 Rh5 20. Qf4 Rf5 21. Qe3 Rh5 22. b3 $16 {White has targets on both flanks
while black has no counterplay at all.} a6 23. Bd2 Kd7 24. Qe2 Na5 25. Rfb1 Kc7
26. Ne3 Qd7 27. Bc1 (27. Ng4 {and Nf6 also comes in consideration}) 27... Qc6
28. Ng4 Nd7 29. Bf4 Kd8 30. Qe3 Ke8 31. b4 Nb7 32. a4 Nd8 (32... bxa4 {was the
only defense but after} 33. Ra2 {clearly black will suffer}) 33. Bg5 $18 Nb6
34. axb5 axb5 35. Bxe7 Kxe7 36. Nf6 Rh8 37. Qg5 Kf8 38. Nxh4 {Total collapse}
Rxa1 39. Rxa1 Na4 40. Ra3 Qc7 41. Nf3 Nc6 42. h4 Ne7 43. h5 gxh5 44. Nxh5 Nf5
45. Nf6 Ng7 46. g3 Qe7 47. Kg2 {1-0 (47) Adams,M (2694)-Lemos,D (2556) Caleta
2010} *

