1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Be7 4. Ngf3 Nf6 5. e5 Nfd7 6. Bd3 c5 7. c3 Nc6 8. O-O
a5 {This move is difficult to crack. Black wants to have a5-a4 at some point
creating counterplay on the queenside and also it takes away the possibility
of Nb3 in some variations. Before I get deeper on this main line I'd like to
let you know what happens if black plays a normal move like 8...00} (8... O-O
9. Re1 Qb6 {in french style} 10. dxc5 Nxc5 11. Bc2 $14 {or 11.Bb1. White will
continue with Nb3, Bf4 and start an attack on the kingside. Without nothing to
attack in the center black lacks counterplay}) 9. a4 {This is the main move
and here black is faced with two options, both equally complicated 9...Qb6 and
9...cxd4} (9. Re1 {is the alternative and one that I have played myself but I
don't recommend it}) 9... cxd4 (9... Qb6 $5 {This is a serious alternative here
} 10. dxc5 $1 Qc7 $1 (10... Nxc5 $6 11. Bc2 Qc7 12. Re1 Nd7 13. Qe2 b6 14. Nb3
Ba6 15. Qe3 O-O-O 16. Nbd4 Bc5 17. Bd2 Kb7 18. Rac1 Rde8 {Fedorchuk,S (2603)
-Giaccio,A (2466) Lorca 2007} 19. b4 $1 {there are other strong moves as well
but this gives white a possibly winning attack}) (10... Bxc5 $6 11. Qe2 f6 12.
exf6 Nxf6 13. Bc2 O-O 14. Nb3 Bd6 (14... e5 15. Qb5 $18 Nd7 16. Nxc5 Qxc5 17.
Bb3 Rxf3 18. gxf3 Qf8 19. Qxd5+ Kh8 20. Qf7 Qxf7 21. Bxf7 {1-0 (21) Hansen,S 
(2566)-Richter,M (2484) Germany 2011}) 15. Be3 Qd8 16. Nfd4 $14 {with the
square b5 available for the white knight white must be better here. Its true
black has the center but it doesn't look that strong and white will put
pressure on it with Rad1 soon}) 11. Nb3 Ndxe5 (11... Ncxe5 12. Bf4 Nxf3+ 13.
Qxf3 Qd8 14. Qg3 O-O 15. Bc7 Qe8 16. Bb5 f6 17. Bxa5 Qf7 18. Bb4 Ne5 19. Nd4
Rd8 20. Rfe1 $16 {Guseinov,G (2643)-Rueetschi,U (2266) Zurich SUI 2017}) 12.
Nxe5 (12. Bf4 $5 {This move has only been played once and in a blitz game but
it deserves close attention. Maybe just as good as 12.Nxe5 or even better}
Nxf3+ 13. Qxf3 e5 14. Bg3 Be6 {Rublevsky,S (2695)-Ram,S (2248) Khanty-Mansiysk
RUS 2013} (14... Qd8 15. Qe2 f6 (15... e4 16. Bb5 {the d5 pawn will suffer.})
16. Rad1 $14) 15. Nd4 $1 $146 Bxc5 16. Qh5 Bxd4 17. cxd4 h6 18. dxe5 {it is
possible that white can claim an advantage here with two bishops and a
potential attack on the kingside} Qb6 19. Kh1 Qd4 20. Qe2 $14) 12... Qxe5 (
12... Nxe5 13. Bf4 $16) 13. f4 Qc7 14. Be3 {we have been following Adams -
Vallejo Gibraltar 2010 and now} g6 (14... Bd7 15. Kh1 Bf6 16. Qc2 (16. Nd4 {
could be one idea to improve the play for white} Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Qd8 18. Bb5 Bxd4
19. cxd4 O-O 20. b3 Bc6 21. Qd2 $14 {white keeps some space advantage although
it is not clear how much better he is. This of course needs test.}) 16... g6
17. Qf2 O-O {Vallejo played against me this way and it's the best for black.}
18. Nd4 Nxd4 19. cxd4 b6 $17 {black is already better. I managed to create
some counterplay and even missed a winning chance later but that's another
story. The game ended in a draw Castellanos, R (2508)-Vallejo, F (2705) Ciudad
de Zaragoza}) 15. Qe1 Bd7 16. Kh1 {This position is difficult to evaluate
properly. Apparently, there are no ruptures on either side which means it will
be difficult to open the position. White may have to go g4-f5 at some point
but this can be double-edged. The queen can go to f2 to prevent any
possibility of b7-b6. In general, I believe the position is double-edged.} h5
$6 {this is just weakening} 17. Nd4 $1 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 O-O 19. f5 $1 Bxc5 20.
Bxc5 Qxc5 21. fxg6 Qe7 22. Qe5 $16 {Adams,M (2694)-Vallejo Pons, F (2705)
Caleta 2010 White has an obvious advantage and went on to win}) (9... g5 {
is rarely seen and you can make a comparison with the line 8...g5 and see what
difference it makes to have a5-a4 included. Nevertheless, here white has a way
to play} 10. Bb5 $5 {with a pawn on a7 this makes little sense but here why
not?} g4 11. Ne1 cxd4 12. cxd4 Nxd4 13. Qxg4 Nxb5 14. Qg7 Rf8 15. axb5 $14) 10.
cxd4 Nb4 {The main move here} 11. Bb5 {This is Adams choice} b6 ({Two key
Michael Adams games to understand what white is trying to play for:} 11... O-O
12. Nb1 Nb6 13. Nc3 Bd7 14. b3 {[%csl Rb6] limiting the N on b6} ({I once
forgot the move order and played} 14. Qe2 {still nothing serious happened} Rc8
15. Bf4 Bc6 16. Rfc1 Na8 17. Qd2 $1 Nc7 18. Bf1 Rb8 19. g3 $5 (19. Qd1 {
sets a nice trap for black} b5 $6 20. Na2 $1 Bd7 21. Nxb4 Bxb4 22. Bd3 {X h7}
Be7 23. Bd2 $16) 19... b5 20. axb5 Nxb5 21. h4 Bd7 22. h5 Nxc3 23. bxc3 Nc6 24.
Bd3 Ra8 25. Bc2 f5 26. exf6 gxf6 {Castellanos,R (2515)-Edouard,R (2688) Cto de
España Dv Honor 2012} 27. Re1 $16) 14... Rc8 15. Bd2 Rc7 16. Qe2 Qa8 17. Rfc1
Rfc8 18. h4 Bxb5 19. axb5 Nd7 20. g3 $14 {This is the kind of position white
is hoping for in this line. With more space he now prepares to advance his
kingside pawns. Black is unable to unblock the C file and provoke a favorable
trade of pieces.} Qa7 (20... h6 21. Kh2 b6 22. Ne1 Nf8 23. Na4 Nd7 24. Bc3 Qb8
25. Ng2 Nf8 26. Ne3 Kh8 27. Qd2 Qb7 28. Re1 Rb8 29. Rac1 Qc8 30. Qe2 Qd7 31.
Bd2 Rxc1 32. Rxc1 Qd8 33. Kg2 Nd7 34. Bxb4 Bxb4 35. Rc6 Kg8 36. f4 {1-0 Adams,
M (2699)-Bradford,J (2409)/Edmonton CAN 2009/The Week in Chess 767}) 21. Kg2
Nf8 22. Qf1 Nd7 23. Na4 b6 24. Rxc7 Rxc7 25. Rc1 Qb7 26. Kh2 Qc8 27. Rxc7 Qxc7
28. Nc3 Qc8 29. Qe2 Qc7 30. Ne1 Nf8 31. Kg2 Nd7 32. Kf1 Nf8 33. Na4 Nd7 34. Bc3
Kf8 35. Ng2 Ke8 36. Nf4 g6 37. Ke1 Kd8 38. Kd1 Kc8 39. Nh3 h6 40. h5 g5 41. Ng1
Kb7 42. Nf3 Qc8 43. g4 Ka7 44. Ne1 Kb7 45. f3 Nf8 46. Nd3 Nxd3 47. Qxd3 f5 48.
exf6 Bxf6 49. Be1 $1 {with idea of Bg3} Qc7 50. Nc3 Be7 51. Ne2 Bd6 52. Bd2 Qf7
53. Ke1 Nd7 54. Kf2 Nf6 55. Kg2 Bc7 56. Be1 Kc8 57. b4 $1 axb4 58. Bxb4 Qd7 59.
Bf8 Qd8 60. Bxh6 Qd6 61. Kf1 e5 62. Qf5+ Nd7 63. Bg7 e4 64. fxe4 dxe4 65. h6
Qe7 66. Qg6 Nf8 67. Bxf8 Qxf8+ 68. Qf5+ {1-0 Adams,M (2703)-Caruana,F (2649)/
Zafra ESP 2009/The Week in Chess 762}) 12. Nb1 Ba6 13. Nc3 O-O 14. Qe2 Bxb5 15.
axb5 Rc8 16. Bd2 {Ni Hua follows Adams ideas} Qc7 17. b3 $1 {X c4 this
prevents an invasion on c4} Qb7 18. Rac1 (18. Rfc1 $142 Rc7 19. h4 Rfc8 20. g3
$14) 18... Rfe8 {This move just turns out to be a waste of time. It is better
to double rooks on the C file immediately} (18... Rc7 $142 19. h4 Rfc8) 19. h4
Bf8 20. h5 h6 21. Nh2 f6 22. f4 $16 Be7 23. Ng4 Kh7 24. Qf3 f5 25. Ne3 {
[%cal Gg2g4]} Nd3 $4 26. Rb1 $2 {Returning the favor} ({White could have won
immediately by} 26. Nexd5 $1 Nxc1 (26... exd5 27. Qxd3 {is resignable}) 27.
Nf6+ Nxf6 28. Qxb7 Nxb3 29. exf6 Bxf6 30. Nb1 $18) 26... Bb4 $2 ({The only
chance was} 26... Nb4 27. g4 $36 fxg4 28. Qxg4 Nf8 29. Rf2 {white is still
better but plenty of work ahead}) 27. Nexd5 ({again white missed a killing blow
} 27. Nxf5 $1 exf5 (27... Bxc3 $2 28. Nd6 {intermediate killer}) 28. Qxd3)
27... Bxc3 28. Nxc3 (28. Nf6+ $1) 28... Qxf3 29. Rxf3 $16 Nb4 30. g4 (30. Rd1
$16 {[%cal Gd2e1,Gd4d5]}) 30... fxg4 31. Rg3 Nc2 {After many mistakes the
position is no longer clear and black is not even worse. I think it's a good
moment to stop analyzing in detail already.} 32. d5 exd5 33. Rxg4 d4 34. Ne4
Na3 35. Re1 Nxb5 36. e6 Nc5 37. f5 Nxe4 38. Rexe4 Rc5 39. Ref4 Nd6 40. f6 gxf6
41. Rxf6 Nf5 42. Rf7+ Kh8 43. Rg6 Re5 44. Bf4 Rd5 45. Rgf6 d3 46. Rxf5 Rxf5 47.
Rxf5 Rxe6 48. Kf2 Re4 49. Bxh6 Rb4 50. Bd2 Rxb3 51. h6 a4 52. Rf8+ Kh7 53. Rf7+
Kh8 54. Rc7 {1-0 (44) Ni Hua (2692)-Cvek,R (2518) Ohrid MKD 2009 The Week in
