1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Be7 4. Ngf3 Nf6 5. e5 Nfd7 6. Bd3 c5 7. c3 Nc6 8. O-O
g5 $5 {For many years and up to this day this move is one of the most
problematic for white. It leads to very complicated positions and if you are
not well prepared you can lose quickly or end up worse} 9. dxc5 $1 {There are
other moves but this is White's main choice and the move I have chosen in the
past too.After this move, black has two main continuations: he can play 9...g4
or 9...Ndxe5 I have decided to analyze them in two different files. Before
continuing with 9...g4 let's have a look at some minor alternatives:} g4 (9...
Nxc5 {is seldom seen and it is not so bad} 10. Bb5 ({besides 10.Bb5 I must
mention} 10. Bc2 $5 {very interesting} g4 (10... Nd7 11. Nb3 $1 g4 12. Nfd4
Ndxe5 $1 (12... Ncxe5 13. f4 gxf3 14. Nxf3 {gives white some dangerous
initiative}) 13. Qe2 h5 14. Bf4 $44 {it is hard to say what comes out of this
and I invite the reader to walk through this unknown path. I believe white has
some good practical compensation} Bd6 15. Bg3 h4 16. Nxc6 Nxc6 17. Bxd6 Qxd6
18. Qxg4 Bd7 19. Qg5 $1 Qe5 $1 20. Qd2 $13) 11. Nd4 Nxe5 12. f4 gxf3 13. N2xf3
Ng6 14. Qe2 $44) 10... Bd7 {this is the safest move and now} (10... Qb6 $5 {
logical and now white should play precise} 11. Nd4 $1 a6 (11... Bd7 12. Bxc6
bxc6 13. b4 Nd3 14. N2b3 {according to GM Arizmendi white is better here and I
agree}) 12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13. b4 Nd7 (13... Nd3 14. N2b3 Nxe5 (14... Nxc1 15. Rxc1
$14) 15. Qh5 $5 $36 h6 16. Bxg5 Bxg5 17. f4 Ng6 18. fxg5 $16 {Arizmendi.}) 14.
Qh5 $1 Nxe5 15. N2f3 $36 (15. N2b3 $5 $36) 15... Ng6 (15... Nxf3+ 16. Nxf3 Bf6
17. Be3 Qb7 18. Bd4 Bxd4 19. cxd4 $16) 16. Bxg5 Bxg5 17. Nxg5 c5 18. bxc5 Qxc5
19. f4 $1 Ra7 (19... Qxc3 20. Rad1 Ra7 21. Nxh7 Re7 22. Nf6+ Kf8 {(d8)} 23. Qg5
$18) (19... h6 20. Ngxe6 Bxe6 21. f5 Bxf5 22. Rae1+ $18) 20. Ne4 $1 Qc7 21.
Nf6+ Ke7 22. f5 Qxc3 23. Rad1 Qe3+ 24. Kh1 Kxf6 25. fxe6+ Nf4 26. Qf5+ {
1-0 Arizmendi Martinez,J (2504)-Herraiz Hidalgo,H (2471)/Sant Lluis 2005/CBM
109}) (10... a6 {this just runs into white's strategy of blockade on the dark
squares} 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. b4 $5 Nd7 13. Nb3 g4 (13... h6 {is better but} 14.
Re1 Qc7 15. Bd2 $1 {is pleasant for white. If black won't take white's central
pawn then he will just play Rc1 and c4}) 14. Nfd4 Nxe5 15. Bf4 $16 Qc7 (15...
Bd6 $142 16. Re1 Qc7 17. Bxe5 Bxe5 18. Qxg4 $14) 16. Bxe5 Qxe5 17. Nxc6 Qf4 18.
Nxe7 Kxe7 19. g3 Qg5 20. Qd4 $18 {complete domination of the dark squares} f6
21. f4 gxf3 22. Rxf3 Bd7 23. Qc5+ Ke8 24. Re1 Rf8 25. Qd6 e5 26. Nc5 Bh3 27.
Ne6 Qd2 28. Qxf8+ {[%emt 0:00:22] 1-0 Smirin,I (2555)-Poldauf,D (2370)/
Groningen 1990/CBM}) (10... Nd7 {this was played by Nakamura a couple of times
but it should be an inferior line} 11. Nb3 h6 12. Nfd4 Ndxe5 13. f4 gxf4 14.
Bxf4 Bd7 {and now} 15. Nxe6 $1 Bxe6 16. Bxe5 Rg8 17. Nd4 Qb6 {Schroeder,J 
(2514)-Kotainy,J (2397) Germany GER 2016} 18. b4 O-O-O 19. Bxc6 bxc6 20. a4 {
white has a winning attack}) 11. Qe2 (11. Re1 {is perfectly playable as well}
Nxe5 $2 {does not work} 12. Nxe5 Bxb5 13. Qh5 O-O $4 (13... Rf8 {is the only
move and now} 14. Ndf3 $16 {white will play Nd4 next or pick a pawn on g5 in
either case with a better position}) 14. Re3 $18 g4 15. Qxg4+ Kh8 16. Rh3 Bg5
17. Qh5 Kg7 18. Ndf3 Bxc1 19. Qxh7+ Kf6 20. Qh4+ Kf5 21. g4+ Ke4 22. g5+ {
1-0 (22) Lorenzo de la Riva,L (2436)-Torrecillas Martinez,A (2407) Catalunya
2013}) 11... a6 12. Bxc6 Bxc6 13. Nd4 $14 {Parligras,M (2605)-Di Paolo,R (2336)
France 2009}) 10. Nd4 Ndxe5 11. Bb5 Bd7 (11... Bxc5 12. Re1 Bd7 13. Bxc6 Nxc6
14. N2b3 Be7 15. Qxg4 $16) (11... h5 {is met with} 12. f4 $16 {white has a
powerful initiative}) 12. N2b3 $5 {The most promising line, we hang on to our
pawn on c5 while free our pieces} Rg8 (12... h5 $5 {is challenging and now
it's important to remember} 13. Qe2 $5 {I like this move over 13.Re1} Ng6 (
13... a6 14. Bxc6 Nxc6 15. Re1 $1 {a key move} Qc7 16. g3 {to play Bf4} Nxd4
17. cxd4 Bb5 18. Qc2 Qd7 19. Na5 Bd8 20. Bd2 Bf6 21. a4 Bc6 22. Be3 O-O 23. Bh6
Rfe8 24. Qd2 Kh7 25. Bf4 Bg7 26. b4 Kg8 27. Nxc6 bxc6 28. Rab1 f6 29. Bd6 $16 {
white has a large advantage Tulfer, P (2493)-Stengelin,M (2412) ICCF email 2011
}) 14. f4 gxf3 (14... Nxd4 $5 15. Bxd7+ $5 (15. Nxd4 Bxb5 16. Qxb5+ Qd7 17. f5
$16 {looks quite good too}) 15... Qxd7 16. Nxd4 $1 {a very important move to
remember} (16. cxd4 Nh4 $1 $17 {[%cal Gh4f5] and black is better}) 16... O-O (
16... Bxc5 17. f5 $36) 17. f5 exf5 18. b4 $16 {black's king is weak}) 15. Nxf3
$14 Qc7 (15... a6 16. Bd3 Rg8 17. Bd2 $16 {with idea of Rae1, Nbd4 looks great
for white}) 16. Bg5 $1 O-O-O {Gonzalez Vidal,Y (2503)-Arizmendi Martinez,J 
(2555) Arinsal AND 2011 and now white should have continued with} (16... Rg8 $5
17. Bxc6 $1 bxc6 (17... Bxc6 18. Bxe7 Qxe7 19. Nfd4 $16) 18. Rae1 $16) 17. Bxe7
Ncxe7 18. Nfd4 Rh7 19. Rf6 $16) (12... Nxd4 13. Bxd7+ Qxd7 14. cxd4 Nc6 15.
Qxg4 Bf6 {Saltaev,M (2525) -Ghane Gardeh,S (2265)/Teheran 1998/EXT 1999} 16.
Rd1 h5 17. Qf3 $16 {it is safe to say here that white stands better. Bf4 is
coming and the black king has no safe haven}) 13. Re1 Nc4 (13... Nxd4 14. Nxd4
Bxb5 15. Nxb5 $36 {black's position looks risky without anywhere to hide his
king}) 14. Bf4 $1 Nxd4 ({The point is that} 14... Nxb2 $2 {loses immediately
after} 15. Qc2 Nc4 16. Qxh7 Rf8 17. Qh5 {e6 pawn is under pressure} Qc8 18.
Nxc6 Bxc6 19. Nd4 $18 {white has winning threats}) 15. Nxd4 Rc8 {We continue
to analyze the rest of the game but here black is already under a lot of
trouble, his position might be already lost.} (15... Bxc5 {does not help} 16.
Nxe6 $1 fxe6 17. Qxd5 Bxf2+ 18. Kh1 $1 Kf7 (18... Bxe1 $4 19. Qxe6+) 19. Qh5+
Rg6 20. Re2 $16) 16. b3 $5 {Not a bad move but black missed a brilliant win} (
16. Rxe6 $3 {this is just crushing} Bxb5 17. Re2 $1 {with the threat of Nf5}
Rxc5 (17... Bc6 18. Nf5) (17... Bd7 18. Bd6 Be6 19. Nxe6 fxe6 20. Rxe6 Rg7 21.
Qxd5 $18) 18. b4 Rc6 19. Nxb5 $18) 16... Na3 17. Bd3 Rxc5 18. Bxh7 Rg7 19. Bd3
(19. Bf5 $5 {is also strong} Rxc3 $6 20. Bh6 Rg8 21. Bh7 Rh8 22. Qxg4 $18)
19... Rxc3 20. Be5 (20. Bh6 $1 Rg8 21. Bh7 Rh8 22. Qxg4 $18) 20... Bf6 (20...
Rg5 {was the only move} 21. Qd2 Rc8 $16) 21. Qd2 $1 $18 Bxe5 22. Rxe5 Qc7 23.
Rh5 Rg8 24. Rh7 e5 25. Nf5 e4 26. Qg5 {1-0 (26) Smirin,I (2649)-Akobian,V 
