1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Be7 4. Ngf3 Nf6 5. e5 Nfd7 6. Bd3 c5 7. c3 Nc6 8. O-O
g5 $5 9. dxc5 Ndxe5 {this the most solid option for black and the move that
worries me the most} 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 {Here I would like to suggest two ways of
playing the position for white. One that leads to quiet positions and other
more unbalanced. I have found no advantage in neither so I'll present my
analysis} 11. Nb3 (11. Bb5+ {is the alternative and now} Bd7 12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 $1
(12... Nxd7 13. b4 b6 14. c4 $1 {lead to an advantage for white} dxc4 15. Nxc4
bxc5 16. Nd6+ Bxd6 17. Qxd6 Qb6 18. Qg3 cxb4 19. Qxg5 Qc5 20. Qg3 $36 {white
the black king so exposed is clear that black has permanent problems. 1-0 (33)
Rublevsky,S (2670)-Morozevich,A (2678) Togliatti 2003}) 13. Nf3 Nxf3+ 14. Qxf3
e5 (14... Rc8 15. b4 b6 {Jakovljevic,V (2420)-Vavrak,P (2488) Budva 2009 and
now} 16. Qh5 (16. cxb6 axb6 17. a4 $5) 16... bxc5 17. Bxg5 Bxg5 18. Qxg5 Qe7
19. Qh6 Qf8 20. Qf4 $14 {Jakovljevic,V (2420)-Vavrak,P (2488) Budva 2009}) 15.
Re1 Qe6 16. b4 $11 {this position is roughly balanced but there is plenty of
tension here. White wants Be3 followed by Rad1, on the other hand, black needs
to find somewhere safe for his king and manage his central pawns.} f6) 11...
Nxd3 $1 {gaining permanent values and unbalancing the fight. Black takes the
bishop pair} (11... Qc7 {Is the old move and one that I think allows white to
have a pleasant edge} 12. f4 Bxc5+ 13. Nxc5 Qxc5+ 14. Rf2 $1 {A middlegame
with opposite color bishops is in the horizon and white's dark square bishop
seems much more active} Nxd3 (14... Ng6 15. f5 $5 ({the greedy} 15. fxg5 $16 {
is also possible}) 15... Ne5 (15... exf5 16. Qe2+ Be6 17. Bxg5 $16) 16. fxe6
Bxe6 17. Bxg5 $16) 15. Qxd3 Bd7 {is similar to the game above, white plays on
the dark squares} (15... g4 {was played by the specialist on the French
Grandmaster Sergey Volkov but I think black's position is worse and white can
play in more than just one way} 16. b3 $5 (16. Qg3 $5 {has a tricky idea} Rg8
17. Be3 Qe7 18. f5 exf5 19. Rd1 Be6 20. Bxa7 $14 {the black king is stuck in
the center, forever}) 16... Bd7 17. Be3 Qb5 18. Qd4 Rg8 19. f5 exf5 20. Qe5+
Be6 21. Rxf5 O-O-O 22. Rf2 a6 23. Bf4 Qc6 24. Rd1 b5 {was seen in Iordachescu,
V (2563)-Volkov, S (2636)/Moscow 2007 and now white could have obtained a
large advantage by the forced sequence} 25. Qb8+ Kd7 26. Qa7+ Ke8 27. Re1 $16 {
the point is that} Qxc3 $4 28. Bd2 $18 {and f7 hangs}) 16. Be3 Qc4 (16... Bb5
$6 17. Qd2 Qe7 18. fxg5 $16 (18. a4 $16)) 17. Qxc4 dxc4 18. fxg5 $16 {despite
the trade of queens which gives black certain king safety the endgame is grim
for him} e5 19. Bc5 (19. Re1 $5) 19... Rg8 20. h4 b6 21. Bd6 e4 22. Be5 e3 23.
Rf4 Be6 24. Rd4 Rd8 25. Rad1 Rxd4 26. Rxd4 f5 27. Kf1 Kf7 28. Ke2 Kg6 29. Kxe3
Re8 30. Kf4 $18 {Mamedov,R (2626)-Bartel,M (2609) Novi Sad SRB 2009 The Week
in Chess 782 [Castellanos,R]}) (11... Bd7 {is met with the energetic} 12. f4 $1
Nxd3 13. Qxd3 h6 (13... g4 14. f5 {is good for white}) (13... b6 14. Be3 {
keeping the control on the dark squares in the center looks like the best}) 14.
Be3 Qc7 15. Bd4 {[%csl Gd4]} Rf8 {we are following the game Hracek,Z (2595)
-Stellwagen,D (2524)/Germany 2005} 16. fxg5 {was the move played in the game} (
16. f5 $1 $146 {is an interesting novelty} exf5 (16... e5 17. f6 $16 exd4 18.
Rae1) 17. Rae1 Be6 18. Rxf5 O-O-O (18... Bxf5 19. Qxf5 $40 {[%cal Gf5f6,Gf6h6]
white has a strong attack}) 19. Rf2 $14 {white managed to destroy black's
center and keeps pressure} (19. Rff1)) 16... hxg5 17. Rae1 O-O-O (17... f5 18.
c4 dxc4 19. Qxc4 $14) 18. Qh7 $1 Be8 19. Rf2 {black simply has some problems
to put his central pawns in motion} a5 20. Be5 Qd7 21. Bg7 a4 22. Bxf8 Bxf8 23.
Qg8 Be7 24. Nd4 Bxc5 25. Qxg5 Qc7 26. a3 $18 {Hracek,Z (2595)-Stellwagen,D 
(2524)/Germany 2005}) (11... a5 $5 {In this move order I suggest white plays}
12. Bc2 $5 $146 {with the idea of meeting} a4 13. Nd4 Bxc5 14. Qh5 $36 {
white has some initiative here}) 12. Qxd3 a5 $1 $146 {Vocaturo is always well
prepared and this move brings new hopes for black in this variation} (12... e5
13. Qe2 {is critical for the development of this variation} Qc7 (13... f6 14.
Qh5+ Kd7 $1 {this is regarded as the best move but in my opinion, it's
difficult for black to play with the king in the center} (14... Kf8 15. h4 Kg7
16. hxg5 fxg5 17. Re1 e4 (17... Bf6 $2 {allows white this beautiful combination
} 18. Rxe5 $3 Bxe5 19. Bxg5 Qe8 20. Bh6+ Kf6 21. Qg5+ Kf7 22. Re1 $18 {white
has a winning attack}) 18. Be3 $16) 15. c4 $5 (15. Re1 Kc7 16. Qe2 (16. Be3 $5)
16... Qg8 17. Be3 Bd7 18. Na5 $14) (15. Rd1 Qg8 16. Be3 Kc7 17. Qe2 Be6 18. Na5
Qf7 19. b4 Rhd8 20. a4 $16 {was better for white in 1-0 (39) Borisek,J (2543)
-Mazi,L (2332) Ljubljana 2011}) 15... Kc7 16. cxd5 Qxd5 17. Be3 Bd7 18. Na5 $1
{stopping Bc6 and freeing the B pawn} g4 $1 19. Rfd1 Qe6 20. b4 $13 {the game
is unclear. White has some ideas based on c5-c6 or even f4 but I'm sure black
is not without chances}) 14. Re1 e4 15. Qh5 $14 {with the idea of Be3-d4 The
black pawns are not strong once they have advanced}) 13. f4 O-O 14. Qg3 Qc7 15.
Be3 f6 16. Rf3 {This looks wrong} (16. Rae1 {could be an improvement for white}
Bd7 (16... a4 17. Nd4 Bd7 18. Kh1 Rae8 19. h4 Kh8 20. hxg5 fxg5 21. Ne2 Bf6 22.
