1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. c3 c5 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. Ngf3 Qb6 8. O-O
{I take the liberty to call this line Korchnoi's gambit because he played it a
long time ago with white and simply crushed his opponent, but I don't know if
this line has any specific name} cxd4 9. cxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Nf3 Qb6 {
This gambit offers white a long-term compensation in return for the minimal
material investment. I wouldn't say that white is better, or that there is a
direct route to a clear advantage here but we have a complicated game with
good chances to take over the initiative. My only advice for you in this line
is to play for development and keep the logic thinking, the returns of this
pawn sacrifice can take a long while to show.} 12. Qa4 {this is the main move
and the one that Korchnoi played. I must tell you that white has also several
other moves that lead to the same type of positions} (12. a3 $5 {I like this
move order too} Nc5 {looks aggressive but it hasn't scored well in practice
although I have found some defensible setup for black} 13. Bc2 a5 14. Qd4 a4
15. Be3 Bd7 16. Rac1 Bb5 17. Rfe1 $44 {Iordachescu,V (2555)-Gendre,K (2221)
Naujac 2002 Black could now play} Qc7 18. Qg4 {black has a strong knight on c5
and can defend it with b6 later, white has enough compensation for the pawn
due to black's problems with his king.}) (12. Qc2 {is a serious idea too} h6 (
12... Qc5 13. Qe2 {see the main line}) 13. Bf4 Nc5 14. Be3 Bd7 15. Rac1 Rc8 16.
Qd2 Qd8 17. Bb1 Be7 18. Nd4 $44 {with the plan of f4-f5 Zapolskis,A (2375)
-Jorgensen, M Dos Hermanas 2004}) (12. Rb1 {has also been tried. The highest
rated game in this line went like this} Nc5 13. Bc2 Be7 14. Be3 Qd8 15. Qd4 O-O
16. Rfd1 Bd7 17. Qg4 {I already like white's chances in this position} g6 18.
Bh6 f5 (18... Rc8 {hoping for Bxf8 is an idea but white can certainly try} 19.
h4 {with an attack}) 19. exf6 Rxf6 20. Ne5 $16 {Mamedov,N (2610)-Housieaux,D 
(2423) Cappelle la Grande 2010 This 12.Rb1 could be a good practical option
outside the main roads of the Korchnoi Gambit}) 12... Qb4 {recognized as the
main move for black but not the only one. 12...Be7 is, of course, a serious
possibility here} (12... Be7 13. Qg4 (13. a3 {is less forced and best
practical chance in my opinion but the lines after 13.Qg4 are fun and
instructive}) 13... g6 14. Bh6 $1 {I suggest this sharp move here with two
main ideas for black} Nc5 {this is the safest} (14... Qb4 15. Qh3 Nc5 16. Rad1
$44 {with idea of Bg7}) (14... Qxb2 {is critical and now} 15. Rab1 (15. Rfc1 $5
Qa3 16. Bf1 Qb4 17. Qg3 {just gives white a position in which he is
threatening Rb1 next and black can't move. Unfortunately black has one resource
} Bf8 18. Rab1 Qxb1 19. Rxb1 Bxh6 $14 {hard to tell if white's advantage is
enough to win, black is very solid}) 15... Qxa2 (15... Nxe5 $4 16. Nxe5 Qxe5
17. Bb5+ Bd7 18. Bxd7+ Kxd7 19. Qa4+ {black gets mated}) 16. Qf4 Qa3 17. Ng5
Bxg5 18. Bxg5 a6 (18... O-O 19. Bf6 Nxf6 20. exf6 Kh8 21. Rb4 $3 {wins} Rg8 22.
Qh4 d4 23. Rxd4 Qf8 24. Re1 {with a decisive attack, the threat is Re5!
followed by Qxh7! Have fun finding the mate}) 19. Bf6 Nxf6 20. exf6 Qc3 21. h4
(21. Rfc1 g5 22. Qd6 Qxf6 23. Rc7 Qd8 24. Qc5 {despite being down 4 pawns here
white is pressing}) 21... e5 22. Rfe1 Be6 23. Rxe5 Rc8 24. Rxe6+ (24. Be2 $16)
24... fxe6 25. Qd6 Qxf6 26. Rxb7 Rd8 27. Qc7 e5 28. Bc2 Kf8 29. f4 $3 {a
brilliant move} exf4 30. Qc5+ Rd6 (30... Kg8 31. Bb3 {wins}) (30... Qd6 {
is now met with} 31. Qd4 Rg8 32. Rb6 Qc7 33. Rf6+ (33. Qf6+ $18) 33... Ke7 34.
Rxa6 $18) 31. Rd7 Qe6 32. Qc8+ Qe8 33. Qxe8+ Kxe8 34. Rxd6 Ke7 35. Rxa6 Rc8 36.
Bb3 d4 37. Re6+ Kd7 38. Re4 Kd6 39. Rxd4+ Ke5 40. Rd5+ Kf6 41. Kf2 Rc7 42. Bd1
Ke6 43. Rb5 Rc1 44. Be2 Rc3 45. h5 Rc2 46. h6 Rd2 47. Rb7 Kf5 48. Rxh7 Kg5 49.
Kf3 {1-0 (49) Noble,M (2565)-Sadowski,M (2504) ICCF 2011}) 15. Bc2 Qxb2 16.
Rfc1 Bd7 17. Qf4 f5 18. Rab1 Qa3 $1 (18... Qxa2 $2 19. Bg7 Rg8 20. Qh6) 19. Bg7
Rg8 20. Qh6 Bf8 21. Bxf8 Rxf8 22. Qxh7 O-O-O {with an unclear position. White
can make a draw by} 23. Ng5 Rh8 24. Qe7 Rhe8 25. Qg7 $11 {I believe white has
compensation for the pawn but how much we can't know for sure. Certainly, it's
much more difficult to defend these positions with black}) 13. Qc2 Qc5 (13...
Nc5 $5 {is a good move here and I have faced it a couple of times with bad
results for me} 14. Bd2 Qa4 {and now:} 15. b3 (15. Bxh7 $5 {is the move that I
have played and one that I like} Bd7 (15... Qxc2 {is the critical move} 16.
Bxc2 b6 $11 {with a queenless middlegame which is even but both sides have
their ideas. White would like to advance the H pawn, place a knight on d4 and
so on.}) 16. Rfc1 Be7 17. Be3 b6 18. b3 Qa3 {Castellanos Rodriguez,R (2484)
-Vezzosi, P (2336) Forni di Sopra ITA 2016 and now I should have played} 19.
Bd3 Nxd3 20. Qxd3 Rc8 21. Rxc8+ Bxc8 22. Rc1 Ba6 23. Qb1 Kd7 24. h3 {with an
equal game, perhaps slightly better for white. The ghost of Qh7 at some point
is there.}) 15... Qd7 16. Rac1 {was played by a strong player like Rauf Mamedov
} (16. Nd4 Nxd3 17. Qxd3 $44 b6 18. a4 (18. Qg3 $5 {is one possible idea} Ba6
19. Rfd1 Rc8 20. a4 $44) 18... Bc5 19. b4 {was seen in Istratescu,A (2636)
-Berg,E (2587) Achaea 2012 and now black could try} Ba6 $5 $13) (16. Be2 {
is popular as well but does not promise any clear route to an advantage.} b6 (
16... Be7 17. Be3 b6 18. b4 Qa4 19. Qb2 Nd7 20. a3 Ba6 21. b5 Bb7 22. Rfc1 Rc8
23. Bd1 $1 Qe4 24. Rxc8+ Bxc8 25. Bc2 Qg4 26. h3 Qh5 27. Qc3 Bc5 28. Kh2 d4 29.
Bxd4 Bb7 30. Rd1 Bxf3 31. gxf3 O-O 32. f4 {Kazoks,A (2343)-Johnston,A (2402)
ICCF 2016 The smoke has cleared and the position is equal}) 17. b4 Ba6 18. Bxa6
Nxa6 19. a3 Rc8 20. Qd3 Nb8 21. Rac1 Be7 22. Rxc8+ Qxc8 23. Rc1 Qd7 24. Rc3 O-O
25. Qc2 Na6 26. Nd4 Bd8 27. Nc6 Bc7 28. Rh3 g6 29. Bg5 f6 30. Bxf6 Rf7 31.
Qxg6+ {1-0 (31) Fedorchuk,S (2652)-Suez Panama,G (2047) Schoelcher 2013}) 16...
b6 17. Nd4 Ba6 (17... Nxd3 {is critical} 18. Qxd3 Bc5 {blocking the C file} 19.
Qg3 $5 Kf8 20. Qf4 $44 {white must have compensation with the black king
permanently in the center. How much is unclear.}) 18. Bxa6 Nxa6 19. Qd3 Nc5 20.
Qe2 a5 21. Be3 Be7 22. Qg4 g6 23. Bh6 Bf8 24. Bxf8 Kxf8 25. Qf4 h6 26. Rc3 Qe7
27. Nc6 Qd7 28. Nd4 Qe7 29. Nc6 Qg5 30. Qd4 $13 {Mamedov,R (2660)-Wang Hao 
(2734) Shamkir AZE 2014}) (13... h6 {was the move played against Korchnoi and
he simply crushed his opponent.} 14. Bd2 $1 Qb6 15. Rac1 Be7 16. Qa4 $1 Qd8 17.
Rc2 {development!} Kf8 18. Rfc1 Nb6 19. Qg4 Bd7 20. Ba5 Rc8 21. Rxc8 Bxc8 22.
Bb4 g6 23. Qh4 g5 $6 24. Nxg5 Ke8 25. Bb5+ Bd7 26. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 (26... Bxh4 27.
Ng7#) 27. Qh5+ Kf8 28. Rc3 Rh7 29. Qg6 Rg7 30. Qxh6 Bxb4 31. Rg3 {1-0 (31)
Kortschnoj,V-Udovcic,M Leningrad 1967}) 14. Qe2 (14. Qb1 $5) (14. Qd2 {has
also been played} Qb6 15. Qf4 $44) 14... Qb6 {The queen has to return from the
open C file as it will get attacked again} (14... Be7 15. Be3 (15. Bd2 $5 {
is also possible with similar ideas}) 15... Qc7 (15... Qa5 16. Rac1 O-O 17. Rc3
$5 {poses a nice trap for black, not easy to spot at first sight} Re8 $2 (17...
Qd8 {is better and after} 18. Rfc1 {white's compensation is obvious}) 18. Bxh7+
$1 {and white is already winning} Kxh7 19. Ng5+ Bxg5 20. Qh5+ Kg8 21. Bxg5 Qxc3
22. bxc3 Nxe5 23. f4 {1-0 (23) Kolev,A (2510)-Herraiz Hidalgo,H (2305) Linares
1996}) 16. Rac1 Qd8 17. Rc3 O-O 18. Rfc1 b6 19. b4 $1 $44 a6 {1-0 (56)
Sielecki,C (2390)-Schmitz,M (2104) Germany 2003} (19... Bxb4 $2 20. Bxh7+ Kxh7
21. Ng5+ Kg8 22. Qh5 {white wins}) (19... a5 20. bxa5 bxa5 21. Rc7 $16) (19...
f6 {is best but here black is suffering too for instance} 20. Qc2 Nxe5 21.
Bxh7+ Kh8 22. Nxe5 fxe5 23. Bd2 Bh4 24. Rh3 Qf6 25. Rf1 Ba6 26. Bd3 Rac8 27.
Qb1 Bxd3 28. Qxd3 Kg8 29. g3 e4 30. Qe3 Bxg3 31. Rxg3 $16) 20. Bf4 $16 {
with idea of Nd4 looks good}) 15. a3 (15. Be3 $5 {can be met with} Bc5 {
But white has good practical chances here too} 16. Bf4 (16. Bd2 $5 Bb4 $6 (
16... Qxb2 {is critical} 17. Rab1 Qa3 (17... Qxa2 $4 18. Ra1 Qb2 19. Rfb1 $18)
18. Rfc1 a6 19. Rc3 $1 (19. Bc2 $44 {with idea of Ng5}) 19... Qxa2 20. Rbc1 b6
21. Qd1 $1 {suddenly black is in trouble as Ra1 is a threat} d4 {only move} 22.
Rc4 Bb7 23. Ra1 Bxf3 24. gxf3 Qxa1 25. Qxa1 Nxe5 26. Rxc5 bxc5 27. Qa4+ Ke7 28.
Be4 {black is not lost but definitely white is better}) (16... a5 {is a better
plan with similarity to the main line, locking the queenside with a4}) 17. Bf4
Be7 18. Rac1 a6 19. Rc3 Qd8 20. Rfc1 $14 {white has already a great lead in
development here and black's position is delicate, he went on to win
Karpatchev,A (2469)-Khetsuriani,B (2337) Corfu 2007}) 16... f5 17. exf6 Nxf6
18. b4 Be7 19. Rac1 {draw agreed in Azarov - I. Khenkin, Bad Wiessee 2010 but
no doubt white can continue on playing} O-O 20. b5 Bd6 21. Ne5 Qd8 22. Rfe1 Qe7
23. a4 $44) (15. Qc2) 15... a5 $1 {black can now play this useful move
preventing b4 and still meet Be3 with Bc5} (15... Be7 {allows} 16. Be3 Qd8 17.
Rac1 O-O 18. Rc3 $44 f5 19. exf6 Bxf6 20. Bd4 Bxd4 21. Nxd4 Nf6 22. Nxe6 Bxe6
23. Qxe6+ Kh8 24. Rfc1 Re8 25. Qf5 $14 {Pavasovic,D (2564)-Rozentalis,E (2553)
Austria AUT 2016}) 16. Bd2 (16. Bf4 Nc5 17. Be3 Qd8 {leads to the same thing})
16... Nc5 17. Be3 Qd8 18. Bb5+ Bd7 19. Rac1 Nb3 (19... Rc8 20. Rc3 a4 21. Rfc1
b6 22. Nd4) 20. Rc3 a4 21. Nd4 Nxd4 22. Bxd4 Be7 23. Rfc1 O-O 24. Bxd7 Qxd7 25.
Rc7 {Draw agreed in Kappes,D (2311)-Schubert,W (2187) GER email 2008 Black
equalizes after} Rfc8 26. Rxd7 Rxc1+ 27. Qf1 Rxf1+ 28. Kxf1 Bf8 29. Rxb7 g5 $1
$11 {Conclusion: In my opinion, the Korchnoi Gambit is objectively equal,
black needs to play very precise to avoid a difficult position. In tournament
practice these positions have proven to be difficult, white has many different
ways to play, not only with Qa4 and all lead to the same script, that's why
not many adepts of the French defense are willing to enter in this line.} *

