1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. c3 c5 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. Ngf3 g6 $5 {
This was a fairly decent try against white's system with 7.Ngf3 Black's idea
is to play Bg7-00-followed by f6 with great pressure against white's center.
Therefore white needs to respond energetically with} 8. h4 h6 {This is the
main, solid alternative for black but he has an alternative that could be a
bit of a headache for white. The move 8...Qb6} (8... Qb6 $5 {This move
threatens to win the d4 pawn just like in the Korchnoi gambit but with the
inclusion of the moves h4 / g6. White doesn't have many options here, he must
continue with} 9. h5 $1 {Critical. This move leads to complications that you
better memorize because otherwise, black will crush you. That's what happened
to me against GM Orelvis Perez, I knew 9.h5 was the critical way to go and I
played it and tried to remember the rest of the moves over the game, I failed
and lost the without much effort from my opponent.} Rg8 $5 (9... g5 10. Nxg5
cxd4 11. cxd4 Qxd4 12. Ndf3 Qb4+ 13. Bd2 Qxb2 14. Rb1 Qxa2 $1 {the critical
move} (14... Qa3 {is possible too but here white plays} 15. Bxh7 $1 {this is
the right capture} Nc5 $1 (15... Ndxe5 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Bc2 $1 {This position
has never been played before, I believe white has better chances but the
situation is not one-sided. One possible line is} Bc5 18. O-O Qg3 19. Ba4+ Bd7
20. Bxd7+ Nxd7 21. Rb3 Qc7 22. Rh3 Ke7 23. Re1 $13 {followed by Bc3 or Qf3}) (
15... Be7 16. Bc2 (16. h6 $5) 16... Ndxe5 (16... Nc5 17. h6 Nd3+ 18. Kf1 $16)
17. Nxe5 Nxe5 18. O-O $16 {black has problems with his king}) 16. Qc2 Qa4 (
16... b6 17. Rh4 $1 {with idea of Rf4}) 17. Qxa4 Nxa4 18. Bc2 Nc5 19. Nh7 Be7
20. Nf6+ $16 {It's highly unclear but white's chances seem better here with
two bishops and the H pawn. There is plenty of activity}) 15. Nxh7 Be7 $1 (
15... Ndxe5 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Bb5+ Nc6 18. Nf6+ Kd8 19. Bc3 {wins for white
with the idea of Ra1}) 16. O-O Nc5 17. Bc2 Qc4 $1 {we have been following my
game Castellanos Rodriguez, R (2509)-Perez Mitjans, O (2429) Azuqueca de
Henares ESP 2013 and now:} 18. h6 (18. Bg5 $1 {this looks strong} Bxg5 19.
Nfxg5 Nd4 20. Nf6+ Ke7 21. f4 b6 22. Bh7 Ne2+ 23. Kh2 Ba6 (23... Nc3 {is
strongly met with} 24. Qg4 Nxb1 25. Rxb1 Ba6 $2 26. Nxf7 $1 Rxh7 27. Nxh7 Qc2
28. Qg7 Kd7 29. Rg1 {and white has a decisive advantage}) 24. Ra1 Bb5 25. Qe1
Qc3 26. Qh4 Qg3+ 27. Qxg3 Nxg3 28. Kxg3 Bxf1 29. Rxf1 a5 30. f5 Raf8 31. Kh4 d4
32. g4 d3 33. Bg6 {1-0 (33) Lifanov,V (2424)-Florian,J (2423) ICCF 2014}) 18...
b6 $1 (18... Qg4 19. Nf6+ Bxf6 20. exf6 Qh5 21. h7 e5 22. Nxe5 $1 Qxe5 23. Re1
Ne4 {Asis Gargatagli, H (2458)-Perez Mitjans, O (2418) Barcelona 2013} 24. Bxe4
dxe4 25. Qa4 {would have given white a winning attack, for example} Qxf6 26.
Qxe4+ Be6 27. Rxb7 $18) (18... Ne4 19. Bxe4 dxe4 20. Rc1 Qd5 21. Nfg5 {gives
white a strong initiative.}) 19. Re1 Ba6 20. Nf6+ Bxf6 21. exf6 O-O-O 22. Rc1
Qg4 23. Ng5 Qxd1 24. Bxd1 Rdf8 25. h7 $14 {the position is a mess but white's
activity should give him an edge}) 10. Kf1 {This is a fantastic idea and still
''new'' as there aren't many games with it.} cxd4 (10... Be7 11. dxc5 $5 (11.
Rb1 $5 a6 12. a3 cxd4 13. cxd4 Nxd4 14. hxg6 hxg6 15. Nxd4 Qxd4 16. Nf3 Qb6 17.
Be3 {is a version of the Korchnoi Gambit that favors white, for example} Bc5
18. Bxc5 Nxc5 19. Kg1 {with Rh7 coming soon}) (11. a3 $5 {makes sense too})
11... Nxc5 (11... Qc7 12. Nb3 Ndxe5 13. Bf4 $18 {the point of Kf1 can be seen
here, no discover check}) 12. Nb3 Nxd3 13. Qxd3 Bd7 14. Kg1 $13 {white will
try to seize control over the dark squares. Looks reasonable}) 11. cxd4 g5 {
Ragger,M (2659)-Hovhanisian, M (2466) Hersonissos GRE 2017} (11... Nxd4 12.
Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Nf3 Qb6 14. hxg6 hxg6 15. Qa4 {in the spirit of the Korchnoi
Gambit} Qb4 16. Qc2 Nc5 {does not work the same because} 17. Rh4 $1 Qb6 18. Be3
Qc6 19. Be2 $16) {Here white could defend his center with} 12. Nb3 $5 h6 (12...
g4 13. Bxh7 Rh8 14. Ng5 $18) 13. Be3 a5 14. a4 Nb4 15. Bb5 $16 {white has a
big space advantage}) (8... Bg7 9. h5 f6 $6 {this did not work out well at all}
(9... O-O {is the best. I recommend} 10. Kf1 Qb6 11. Rh4 $16 {followed by Kg1})
10. hxg6 fxe5 11. Rxh7 $1 Rxh7 12. gxh7 e4 13. Bxe4 $18 {any capture on e4
would have given white a winning game} dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nf6 15. Bg5 Qd5 16. Nxf6+
Bxf6 17. Qd3 {1-0 (17) Najer,E (2562)-Visser,Y (2378) Groningen 1999}) 9. Bc2
$5 {The idea of this move is to be able to defend the d4 pawn by means of Nb3.
I'll point out a couple of alternatives:} (9. Qe2 {I'll take this as a second
choice, our idea is to defend with Qe3} cxd4 $146 (9... Bg7 10. Nf1 Qa5 (10...
O-O {this is risky} 11. h5 g5 $2 (11... cxd4 $142) 12. Bxg5 $1 hxg5 13. h6 Bh8
14. h7+ Kg7 15. Nxg5 $3 Qxg5 16. Rh5 Qxh5 (16... Qxg2 17. Ne3 Qg1+ 18. Kd2 $18)
17. Qxh5 $16 Re8 18. Ne3 b6 19. Ng4 Kf8 20. Nh6 Nd8 21. Ng8 {1-0 Fluvia
Poyatos,J-Mayo Martinez,M/Calella de Palafrugell 2004}) 11. Bd2 Qb6 12. Be3
cxd4 13. cxd4 Qb4+ 14. N1d2 (14. Qd2 $5) 14... Qxb2 15. O-O Qa3 16. Nb3 Qe7 17.
Rac1 $44 {white has compensation for the material deficit and managed to win
the game. Bauer,C-Gleizerov,E/Biel SUI 2009}) 10. cxd4 Nb4 11. Nb1 $1 (11. Bb1
$2 b6 {with Ba6}) 11... Nxd3+ 12. Qxd3 Nb8 {Black tries to develop his
queenside bishop but white finds a nice wait to keep it shut down} 13. Nc3 b6
14. O-O Qd7 (14... Ba6 15. Nb5) 15. Nb5 a5 16. a4 Nc6 17. Bd2 Nb4 $6 ({better
is} 17... Ba6 18. Rfc1 $14) 18. Qc3 Kd8 {we can see that black has real
problems in this position. Gonzalez, Y-Gleizerov, E La Laguna open 2010 Now}
19. Nh2 $16 {trying to exploit the weak squares on the kingside is worth a try}
) (9. Bb1 {this has the same idea as 9.Bc2} b5 (9... Qb6 10. Nb3 cxd4 11. cxd4
a5 12. a4 {leads to a position in which there is no central tension and white
keeps a space advantage. Let's see some examples:} Ndb8 (12... Nb4 13. Be3 Qc7
14. Nc1 b6 15. Ne2 Ba6 16. O-O Rc8 17. Ra3 $1 {enabling Rc3} Nb8 18. Rc3 Qd7
19. Re1 (19. h5 gxh5 (19... g5 20. Nh2 {[%cal Gh2g4]}) 20. Re1 $14) 19... N8c6
20. h5 {A typical idea that weakens the square g4} g5 21. Nh2 Bg7 22. Ng4 Ne7
23. f4 gxf4 24. Bxf4 {[%csl Rh6]} Rc4 {black actually managed to win this game
in Tjurin, A (2341)-Visser, Y (2480)/Pardubice 2005 but the opening has been a
success for white, he could have continued with} 25. Nf6+ Bxf6 26. exf6 Nc8 (
26... Nec6 27. Re3 {[%cal Gb2b3]} Na7 28. Ng3 Kd8 29. b3 Rc6 30. Nf5 $18) 27.
Ng3 Nd6 28. Qg4 Kd8 29. Qg7 Re8 30. Bxd6 Qxd6 31. Nf5 Qc7 32. Rxc4 dxc4 33.
Nxh6 $18) 13. O-O Be7 14. Be3 Na6 15. Bd3 Bd7 16. g3 (16. Bb5 $14 Nc7 17. Be2
Na6 18. Qd3 $14 {[%cal Yf1c1] with the idea of Rfc1}) 16... Rc8 17. Nfd2 Ncb4
18. Bb1 h5 19. Kg2 Qc7 20. Qe2 Qb6 21. Nf3 Rc6 22. Qd2 Qc7 23. Rc1 Rc4 24. Bg5
$14 {1-0 (50) Rasik,V (2469)-Chytilek,R (2392)/Czechia 2006/EXT 2007 (50)}) 10.
a3 (10. Nf1 b4 {gives black the possibility of Ba6}) 10... a5 11. Nf1 b4 $6 (
11... Ba6 {was better and now} 12. h5 (12. Ng3 $5 b4 13. Bd3 Qb6 14. Be2 $13)
12... g5 13. Ne3 cxd4 14. cxd4 b4 $1 15. Bd3 Qb6 16. Bxa6 Qxa6 17. Ng1 $1 {
this move is necessary unfotunately} Bg7 18. Ne2 f6 19. exf6 Nxf6 20. axb4 (20.
O-O O-O) 20... Nxb4 21. O-O O-O 22. Bd2 Qb6 $13) 12. axb4 cxb4 13. h5 $1 g5 14.
Ne3 {Going to g4} Ba6 15. Ng1 $5 {a little bit of an extravagant operation but
not bad} (15. Bd3 {was naturally good} Qb6 16. O-O Bxd3 17. Qxd3 Qa6 18. Qd1
$14 {black is suffering on the kingside.}) 15... Qb6 16. Ne2 Qb5 17. f4 $132 {
In this complicated position black went wrong} gxf4 $2 (17... Qxe2+ {was
necessary but it is not an easy decision to make} 18. Qxe2 Bxe2 19. Kxe2 gxf4
20. Ng4 a4 $1 $132 {this is the key move, ensuring black some counterplay
against white's pawn chain} 21. Bxf4 a3 22. Be3 Rb8 23. bxa3 bxc3 24. Rc1 Rb2+
25. Kf3 Rd2 $1 {another key move} 26. Rxc3 (26. Bxd2 cxd2 $15) 26... Nxd4+ 27.
Kf4 Ne2+ 28. Kf3 Nxc3 29. Bxd2 Nb5 {black is definitely not worse.}) 18. Nxf4
$16 {now white is threatening Bd3 and 00 which makes his position much better
already Smirin, I (2676)-Abbasov, F (2529) Baku AZE 2011}) 9... b5 ({Much more
interesting is} 9... Bg7 $5 10. Nf1 $5 $13 {with the idea that} O-O $2 (10...
b5 11. Ng3 a5 12. O-O cxd4 13. cxd4 Qb6 14. Be3 Ba6 15. Nh2 {with the center
stable white is always a bit better. I find it hard to like black's position}
O-O-O 16. Ng4 h5 17. Nh2 Kb8 18. Nf3 Rc8 19. Ne2 Rc7 20. Ng5 Nd8 21. Nf4 Nf8
22. Nd3 Nd7 23. b4 a4 24. Nc5 Bb7 25. Bd3 Nf8 26. Qe2 Bc6 27. Rfc1 Be8 28. Rc2
{1-0 (28) Caruana,F (2709)-Dvirnyy,D (2492) Siena ITA 2010 A good masterclass
from Caruana}) 11. h5 g5 12. Bxg5 $1 hxg5 13. h6 Bh8 14. Qd3 $18 {winning}) (
9... b6 {This is probably the way to go for black} 10. O-O Ba6 11. Re1 cxd4 12.
cxd4 Nb4 (12... g5 $5) 13. Nb1 (13. Bb1 g5 $5 $132) 13... Qc7 14. Nc3 Nxc2 15.
Qxc2 O-O-O (15... Bg7 $5) 16. Bf4 Kb7 $13 {Gopal, G-Ghane Garden, S/
Vishakapatnam 2008}) 10. O-O a5 11. Re1 cxd4 12. cxd4 g5 {Black re-activates
the idea of undermining the defense of d4 by attacking the knight on f3} 13.
Nf1 (13. hxg5 {was suggested by M.Adams so we take his advice here} hxg5 14. g4
Be7 15. Nf1 Nb6 16. Ng3 $14 {I like white's chances here with the obvious plan
of Kg2 and Rh1}) 13... g4 14. N3h2 h5 15. g3 Qb6 16. Be3 $14 {We can make a
stop here and say that white's opening has been a success. Black has failed to
create active play and with the center, well defended white has very little to
worry about.} Bb4 17. Re2 Ba6 18. Rc1 O-O-O 19. f3 $1 gxf3 20. Nxf3 Be7 21. Rf2
Kb7 22. Ng5 Bxg5 23. hxg5 Rdf8 24. Rf4 Qd8 25. Rh4 (25. Bd3 $1 Nb6 26. b3 $16 {
Adams,M}) 25... Nb6 26. b3 b4 27. Nh2 Nc8 28. Bb1 N8e7 29. Rxh5 Rxh5 30. Qxh5
Qb6 31. Rc5 Nb8 32. Qf3 Nd7 33. Rc1 Nc6 34. Qf2 Rc8 35. Ng4 Rc7 36. Kh2 a4 37.
Nh6 axb3 38. axb3 Na5 39. Rxc7+ Kxc7 40. Bc2 Bc4 41. Nxf7 Nxb3 42. g6 Qb8 43.
Nh6 Qh8 44. Qf7 Nxd4 45. g7 Qxg7 46. Qxg7 Nxc2 47. Bc1 Ne1 48. Qe7 {1-0 (40)
Adams,M-Berg,E Crete 2007} *

