1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 ({This line we analyze here can also be reached
by a different move order} 3... a6 4. Ngf3 Nf6 5. e5 Nfd7 6. Bd3 c5 7. c3 Nc6)
4. e5 Nfd7 5. c3 c5 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. Ngf3 a6 $5 {let's not underestimate this
move. Although it is not to be feared we still need to take it seriously} 8.
Bc2 $5 {this is my recommendation, for practical purposes.} ({After} 8. O-O {
black can play} g5 $13) (8. Bb1 {can be tried too}) 8... cxd4 {Releasing the
tension too early is never a good idea so believe this is dubious already} (
8... b5 9. O-O Qc7 $6 10. Re1 h6 11. dxc5 (11. Nf1 $5) 11... Bxc5 12. Nb3 Be7
13. Nbd4 $14 {was clearly better for white. The point is that} Ndxe5 $6 14.
Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Bf4 Bd6 {Jones,G (2550)-Sengupta,D (2466)/Canberra AUS 2009;
white can take over the initiative with} 16. Qh5 $1 {[%csl Re6]} Nf3+ (16... g6
17. Qxe5 $1 {white wins}) 17. gxf3 $1 Bxf4 18. Nxe6 Bxe6 19. Rxe6+ Kf8 20. Qxd5
$16 Rd8 21. Qf5 $16 {black is not without defense, but it is clear that white
is on top}) (8... Be7 9. O-O Qb6 10. Nb3 {This is the idea behind Bc2} (10.
dxc5 Qc7 $5) 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 a5 12. Be3 (12. a4 $14 {as we have seen in
previous lines the square b4 is not so relevant}) 12... Qd8 (12... a4 {is
critical} 13. Nc1 $1 Qxb2 14. Rb1 Qa3 15. Re1 {with the threat of Bd2-Re3} Bd8
(15... Bb4 16. Bd2 Bxd2 17. Qxd2 O-O 18. Ne2 $44) 16. Bg5 $44 (16. Bd2 $5)) 13.
Nc1 b5 14. Nd3 Ba6 15. Rc1 h6 16. Nf4 Qb6 17. Bd3 Nb4 18. Bb1 Nc6 19. Re1 $14
b4 {Wong,R-Akopian, T/USA 1993} 20. Nd2 $1 $16 {following with Qg4} (20. Nh5
$16)) 9. cxd4 a5 (9... Qb6 10. Nb3 a5 11. a4 $14 Bb4+ 12. Bd2 $14) 10. O-O Be7
(10... Qb6 {now can be answered not with 11.Nb3 but with} 11. Nb1 $1 {and the
knight is on the way to b5} g5 $5 12. Bxg5 Qxb2 13. Nbd2 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Qxd4 15.
Qh5 {with the initiative}) 11. Nb1 $5 b5 12. Nc3 Ba6 (12... b4 13. Ne2) 13. Re1
h5 $2 {this is too weakening} (13... b4 $142 14. Na4 (14. Ne2 Qb6) 14... Rc8
15. Be3 (15. b3) 15... O-O 16. Rc1 {it's just slightly better for white}) 14.
a4 b4 (14... bxa4 {is a better choice than the move in the game, nevertheless
not enough to equalize} 15. Nxd5 $5 {this is interesting although it seems
that black can defend} (15. h4 $142 $5 {is the safe and better way to play}
Bxh4 16. Bxa4 Ndb8 17. Nxh4 Qxh4 18. Re3 $44) 15... exd5 16. e6 Nb6 {only move}
(16... Nf6 17. Bxa4 $16) (16... fxe6 17. Rxe6 $36) 17. Bxa4 Nxa4 18. Qxa4 Rc8
19. exf7+ Kf8 (19... Kxf7 20. Qxc6 $1) 20. Bg5 (20. b4) (20. Bd2 $13) 20...
Bxg5 21. Re8+ Kxf7 {only move} (21... Qxe8 22. fxe8=Q+) 22. Rxd8 Bxd8 23. b4
$13) 15. Nb5 $16 {The rest of the game is not relevant to our subject} Bxb5 $2
(15... Nb6 16. Bd3 $14 (16. h4 $5) (16. b3 $14)) 16. axb5 Na7 17. Bd3 $16 Qb6
18. Qa4 Bd8 19. Be3 Qb8 20. Nd2 (20. Rec1) 20... O-O $6 21. Qd1 g6 22. Bh6 Re8
23. Re3 Nf8 24. Rg3 h4 25. Rg4 Nxb5 26. Qa4 Nc7 27. Nf3 (27. Qc2) 27... Qc8 28.
Qc2 Qd7 29. Bxf8 Kxf8 30. Bxg6 $18 Na6 (30... fxg6 31. Qxg6 $18) 31. Rf4 Re7
32. Ng5 Rc8 33. Qd2 {1-0 (26) Hansen,S (2551)-Schmittdiel,E (2454) Germany
2005 CBM 106 [Castellanos,R]} *

