1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 (3... h6 {This line we analyze here can also be
reached by a different move order} 4. Ngf3 Nf6 5. e5 Nfd7 6. Bd3 c5 7. c3 Nc6)
4. e5 Nfd7 5. c3 c5 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. Ngf3 h6 $5 {This move has become popular in
recent years, the idea is to play g5 and undermine white's center} 8. Bc2 $5 {
this looks like a good practical choice} ({A decent alternative is} 8. b3 {
there aren't many games with this move so I'll just write some ideas for you
to investigate and check for yourself.} a5 (8... Qb6 9. Bb2 a5 (9... g5 10. O-O
) 10. a4) (8... g5 9. O-O cxd4 10. cxd4 g4 {is critical} (10... h5 11. Bb2 Be7
12. Ne1 Qb6 13. Nc2 Nf8 14. a3 f5 $6 15. exf6 Bxf6 16. b4 $16 {Tarjan,J (2408)
-Ragnarsson, D (2355) Sault Ste. Marie CAN 2017}) 11. Ne1 Nxd4 12. Qxg4 Nc6 13.
Ndf3 Ncxe5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Qe2 Nxd3 16. Nxd3 $44 {white is down a pawn and
black also has the bishop pair, however with the king in the center white has
compensation for the pawn. This needs test}) 9. a4 cxd4 10. cxd4 b6 11. O-O Ba6
12. Bxa6 Rxa6 {Asis Gargatagli, H (2519)-Suarez Gomez, J (2491) Las Palmas ESP
2017} 13. Nb1 $1 $146 {with the idea of Nb5 white has a small edge}) 8... Qb6 {
I believe this is the only critical line} (8... b6 9. O-O cxd4 10. Ba4 $1 Bb7
11. cxd4 $14) 9. Nb3 cxd4 10. cxd4 a5 (10... Nb4 11. Bb1 {doesn't look like
black can exploit the temporary awkward position of white's pieces, for
example:} a5 12. a3 Nc6 13. a4) 11. a4 Nb4 {This does not worry me too much} ({
Black has a critical alternative} 11... Qb4+ $5 {and now} 12. Bd2 $5 {The
problem with this move is that white can't keep his light squares bishop. The
following variation is forced I think} ({The alternative is} 12. Ke2 $5 Qb6 (
12... b5 $2 13. Bd2 Qc4+ 14. Bd3 {this is the point why the king is better on
e2 and not on f1}) 13. Kf1 Nb4 14. Bb1 Qc6 15. Bd2 b5 (15... Nb6 16. Nc1 Nc4
17. Bc3 b5 18. axb5 Qxb5 19. Kg1 a4 20. h4 $14 {with idea of Rh3}) 16. axb5
Qxb5+ 17. Kg1 a4 18. Nc1 Nb6 19. Bc3 Nc4 20. g3 Bd7 21. Kg2 Be7 22. h4 {
Honestly this is unclear and it's hard to say who is better}) (12. Kf1 b5 13.
axb5 Qxb5+ 14. Kg1 Nb4 $15) 12... Qc4 13. Bc3 Nb4 14. Bb1 b6 15. Nc1 Ba6 16.
Nd2 Qc6 17. Qf3 Be7 18. Ne2 Bg5 19. O-O Bxd2 $1 20. Bxd2 Qc4 21. Re1 Nc2 22.
Bxc2 Qxc2 23. Bc3 Rc8 24. Ng3 O-O $13 {The position is roughly even here.}) 12.
Bb1 Qc7 $6 (12... Qa6 {is a better try} 13. Be3 {with the idea of Nc1-e2 or
Nc1-d3 and finally castle would be a good plan} b5 $1 14. O-O bxa4 15. Rxa4 Qb5
16. Ra1 Be7 17. Re1 a4 18. Nc1 Nb6 19. Ne2 $1 Bd7 20. Nc3 (20. Bc1) 20... Qc6
$11) 13. O-O Nb6 14. Re1 $14 {If black fails to put any pressure on white's
kingside then his position is really worse. This game is a good example} Bd7
15. Nc5 Bxc5 16. dxc5 Qxc5 17. Be3 Qc7 18. b3 Rc8 19. Qd4 Na8 20. Qg4 Kf8 21.
Bd2 Qb6 22. Nd4 Nc7 23. Re3 Ne8 24. Rf3 f5 25. Nxf5 h5 26. Nxg7+ Kg8 {1-0 (26)
Jones,G (2644) -Camus de Solliers,G (2346) England 2013} *

