1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. c3 c5 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. Ngf3 {We
analyze here what happens when black plays the same he would play against the
lines with 7.Ne2} cxd4 8. cxd4 f6 9. exf6 Nxf6 (9... Qxf6 {is seldom seen but
it has one idea} 10. O-O Bd6 ({bad is} 10... Nxd4 $143 11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. Nf3
Qf6 13. Re1 $36 {with a strong initiative for the pawn}) 11. Re1 $1 {a very
precise move} h6 {we welcome this move as black just weakens his position} (
11... O-O {has been tried by Ulibin more than once, his idea is to get a
position with opposite color bishops in which black has some practical chances
of a draw} 12. Bxh7+ $1 {the point of 11.Re1} Kxh7 13. Rxe6 Bxh2+ 14. Kxh2 Qf5
15. Nf1 $14 {white is a bit better only, the following example shows how to
play} Kg8 16. Re2 (16. Re1 $1 {is better} Nf6 17. Kg1 Ne4 18. Ng3 Nxg3 19. fxg3
Qh5 20. Qb3 $14) 16... Nf6 17. Kg1 Ne4 18. Ng3 Nxg3 19. fxg3 Qh5 20. Bf4 Bg4
21. Qd3 $2 g5 $1 $17 {and black obtained sufficient counterplay in Navara,D 
(2700)-Ulibin,M (2491) Riga 2014}) 12. Qe2 $14 O-O (12... Nf8 {is the
alternative but now he can't castle}) 13. Qxe6+ Qxe6 14. Rxe6 Bc7 15. Re1 a5
16. b3 a4 17. Ba3 $16 {Hracek,Z (2595)-Jakubiec,A (2485)/Czechia 2006}) 10. O-O
Bd6 11. b3 $5 {From b2 the bishop controls the square e5, and we don't waste
with Re1-Nf1 and so on. I like this quick development} O-O 12. Bb2 Qb6 {
the main move but let's see some alternatives} (12... Qc7 13. Rc1 Bf4 14. g3
Bh6 15. Ne5 $16 {white has a positional advantage}) (12... Bd7 $5 13. Ne5 ({
we can introduce the move} 13. a3 {with the idea of b4-Nb3} a5 14. Ne5 {
is similar to the game but the pawns moves favor white}) 13... Qb6 (13... Nb4
$5 14. Bb1 Be8 15. a3 Nc6 16. Qf3 $5 ({or} 16. Qe2) 16... Qb6 $6 17. Qh3 $14 {
white would be happy to trade the d4 pawn for the e6 pawn} Nxd4 18. Bxd4 Qxd4
19. Qxe6+ Bf7 20. Nxf7 Rxf7 21. Qxd6 Qxd2 22. Bf5 $14 {this may not be much
for white but he can improve as mentioned before.}) 14. Ndf3 {This is our
ideal setup, white is in full control of the position} Rae8 15. Rc1 Re7 16. Re1
Be8 17. h3 $1 Bh5 18. g4 Be8 19. Bb1 Nd7 20. Nxc6 bxc6 21. Ng5 $16 {1-0
Kryvoruchko,Y (2627)-Kraai,J (2502)/Beijing CHN 2008}) 13. Ne5 $1 {Now let's
see a move that black continues to play at all levels even though it is very
bad} Nxd4 $6 ({Better is} 13... Bd7 14. Ndf3 Nb4 15. Bb1 Bb5 16. Re1 $16 {
white has the usual pressure}) 14. Ndc4 $1 {This is a beautiful tactical
operation which gives white a powerful bishop pair} dxc4 15. Nxc4 Bxh2+ {
Only try} (15... Qb4 {is much worse, for example} 16. Bxd4 ({or the simple} 16.
Nxd6 Qxd6 17. Bxd4 $16) 16... Bc7 17. Bb2 {white's piece coordination is much
better}) 16. Kxh2 Qc7+ 17. Kg1 e5 (17... Nc6 {is one way to keep playing up a
pawn. It's reasonable but white's compensation is beyond doubt and he can
fight for the advantage. For example:} 18. Qe2 (18. Qf3 {can also be played})
18... Qf4 19. Rad1 Nb4 20. Be5 Qh6 21. Bd6 Nxd3 {was seen in Diamant,A (2407)
-Rodriguez Vila, A (2533)/Santos BRA 2008 now the simple} 22. Rxd3 Re8 23. Be5
{gives white a decisive advantage. Black can't develop his queenside, if not
by attack white will squeeze positionally for example} Qh5 24. Qxh5 Nxh5 25.
Rc1 {with Nd6 and Rc7 next. This is lost}) 18. Nxe5 $1 Qxe5 19. Bc4+ (19. Bxd4
$16) 19... Kh8 20. Qxd4 $16 {a wide open position with a pair of bishops,
what's not to like?} Qg5 21. Rfe1 Bh3 22. Bf1 Rad8 {losing a pawn but I can't
recommend anything better, the best for black is not get into this position}
23. Qxa7 Nd5 24. Be5 Nb4 25. Qe3 $18 Qxe3 26. Rxe3 Bf5 (26... Nc2 27. Rg3 $1)
27. Rc1 Rf7 28. a3 h6 29. Rf3 Nd5 30. Rc5 Be6 31. Rg3 Ne7 32. Rc7 Rd1 33. Rxg7
{1-0 (33) Smirin, I (2600)-Romero Holmes, A (2465) Las Palmas 1997} *

