1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nc6 {This line was popular years ago but now I
believe it is close to being shut down for good, at least at a high level.} 4.
Ngf3 Nf6 5. e5 Nd7 {now black's idea is to play f6 and recapture with the
queen. Then he will play Bd6 and quickly e6-e5 with good play} 6. Bd3 $1 {
there are other good lines against the Guimard variation but I like this move
that brought me success against GM Igor Naumkin} f6 (6... Nb4 {is the ''safe''
move for black and then} 7. Be2 c5 8. c3 Nc6 {we can transpose to our lines
with 9.Bd3 or take advantage of the extra tempo with} 9. O-O $1 {Qb6 is no
longer an issue since we can always play Nb3. Let's see some examples of what
has been played:} g6 $6 (9... a5 $5 10. a4 Be7 (10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Nb6 12. Nb1
$5 $14 {the usual route to b5}) 11. Nb1 $1 O-O 12. Na3 cxd4 13. cxd4 Nb4 (13...
f6 $5 14. exf6 Nxf6 15. Nb5 Bd7 16. Bd3 $13) 14. Bf4 $1 $14 Nb8 15. Qd2 N8c6
16. Rfc1 Na7 17. Rc3 Bd7 18. Ng5 $1 (18. b3 Rc8) 18... f6 (18... Bxa4 $2 19.
Rh3 h6 20. Nf3 $18 {black can't prevent Bxh6} h5 21. Bh6 $1 $18 (21. Rxh5 $16))
(18... h6 19. Nf3 {[%csl Rh6]} Bxa4 $2 20. Bxh6) 19. exf6 Rxf6 {Petrosian,T 
(2620)-Miroshnichenko,E (2670) Tashkent UZB 2011} (19... Bxf6 20. Nf3 $14 {
the control over the weak square e5 guarantees an edge for white here}) 20. Bc7
Qe8 21. Rg3 Nac6 (21... Bxa4 22. Be5 Bd7 23. Bg4 Nac6 24. Bxf6 Bxf6 25. Nb5 $16
) 22. Nb5 $16 {white is in full control}) (9... Qb6 {[%csl Gb6]} 10. Nb3 $1 a5
(10... cxd4 11. cxd4 a5 12. a4 Be7 13. Bg5 $1 $14 {was better for white
inBenko,P-Laszlo,C/Budapest 1950/EXT 2006}) (10... c4 $6 11. Nbd2 {and soon
white will open with b3}) 11. dxc5 $1 Qc7 (11... Nxc5 12. Be3 a4 13. Nbd4 $14
Qxb2 $6 14. Nb5 Ra5 15. Nfd4 $16) 12. Bf4 Nxc5 13. Nbd4 Bd7 14. Nb5 Qb6 15. Be3
$16 {white has a huge development advantage} Qd8 (15... Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Bxb5 17.
Bxb5+ Qxb5 18. Qf3 $18 {the attack on f7 is deadly}) 16. c4 $1 {opening the
position with the black king in the center} dxc4 17. Bxc4 Qb8 18. Qe2 a4 19.
Rfd1 Na5 20. b4 $1 $18 Nxc4 (20... axb3 21. axb3 $18) 21. Qxc4 Na6 22. Rxd7
Kxd7 23. Rd1+ Ke8 24. Nd6+ Bxd6 25. exd6 Qd8 26. Ng5 {1-0 (26) Geller,E (2600)
-Vaganian,R (2530)/Yerevan 1975/URS-ch} (26. Ne5 $142 $18)) (9... Be7 $5 10.
Re1 O-O 11. Bd3 $5 $14 {with the standard position}) (9... cxd4 10. cxd4 f6 (
10... Nb6 11. Nb3 $1 $14 {Potkin}) 11. exf6 Nxf6 (11... Qxf6 12. Nb3 Bd6 13.
Bg5 $1 $14 {with the idea of Bh4-Bg3}) 12. b3 $5 $146 {I like this idea
planning Bb2-Ne5-Ndf3}) 10. a3 (10. Nb3 $5) 10... Qb6 11. Nb3 Bg7 12. Nxc5 Nxc5
13. dxc5 Qxc5 14. Be3 {Even though this is good enough I also like the direct
14.b4!} (14. Bf4 $14) (14. b4 Qe7 15. Bf4 $14 O-O 16. Rc1 b6 17. Qd2 Bb7 18.
Rfe1 Rac8 19. Qe3 {white dominates the dark squares and has space advantage})
14... Qe7 15. Bb5 Bd7 (15... O-O 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. b4 $14) 16. Bg5 $1 Qc5 17.
Bxc6 bxc6 (17... Bxc6 18. Re1 O-O 19. Qd2 $14) 18. Qd2 O-O 19. h4 (19. Bh6 $14)
19... Rfb8 20. h5 $14 {1-0 (36) Volkov,S (2621)-Miroshnichenko,E (2670)
Nakhchivan AZE 2011}) 7. Ng5 $1 Ndxe5 $1 {The alternatives are worse for black}
(7... fxg5 8. Qh5+ g6 {this loses by force} (8... Ke7 $6 9. Nf3 $16 (9. Nb3 $16
{but 9.Nf3 is stronger}) 9... h6 10. Bxg5+ hxg5 11. Qxh8 $16) 9. Bxg6+ hxg6 10.
Qxg6+ Ke7 11. Ne4 $1 Bh6 (11... Ndxe5 12. Bxg5+ $1 Kd7 13. Nf6+ Kd6 14. dxe5+
Nxe5 15. Bf4 $18) 12. Bxg5+ Bxg5 13. Qg7+ Ke8 14. Qxh8+ Nf8 15. Qh5+ Kd7 16.
Nc5+ Ke7 17. Qxg5+ $18) 8. dxe5 fxg5 9. Qh5+ g6 $1 (9... Kd7 $5 {is the only
playable alternative in this variation} 10. Nf3 Nb4 $1 (10... Qe8 11. Qxg5 Nb4
12. Bb5+ c6 13. Ba4 Qd8 14. Qxd8+ (14. Qf4 Qa5 15. O-O Qxa4 16. c3 Qa5 17. Qf7+
Be7 18. Qxg7 Qd8 19. cxb4 Qg8 20. Qh6 $1 $14) 14... Kxd8 15. a3 Na6 16. c3 Be7
17. h4 Bd7 18. Bc2 Kc7 19. Rh3 h6 {Santos Ruiz,M (2410)-Del Rio de Angelis,S 
(2534) Montcada i Reixac ESP 2016} 20. Be3 $14 {white should definitely have
some edge here. Some ideas with Nd4,h5-g4 and advance the kingside pawns in
the future.}) 11. Bxg5 Nxd3+ 12. cxd3 Qe8 13. Qh4 Qg6 {is not bad for black}
14. Qa4+ c6 15. O-O Qxd3 16. Rac1 {black is better positionally speaking, the
superior pawn structure and the two bishops in the endgame could be deadly,
however i'm not sure how easy this position is to play over the board. This
needs further tests.}) 10. Bxg6+ Kd7 11. c4 $1 {Key move, freeing the c2
square for the bishop} Nxe5 12. Bc2 $44 Qf6 (12... Bd6 $6 {is strongly met with
} 13. f4 $1 Ng6 $5 (13... gxf4 14. c5 Qe8 (14... Bxc5 $142 15. Qxe5 Qh4+ 16. g3
fxg3 17. Qxg3 Qxg3+ 18. hxg3 Bd6 19. g4 $14) 15. Qe2 $16 {1-0 (40) Willemsma,A
(2088)-Zaragatski,I (2469)/Vlissingen NED 2011/The Week in Chess 873 (40)} (15.
Qxe8+ Kxe8 16. cxd6 cxd6 17. Nb3 Rg8 18. Bxf4 Rxg2 19. O-O-O $16)) (13... Nxc4
14. Nxc4 dxc4 15. O-O $36 {can't be suggested for black}) 14. f5 Nf4 15. fxe6+
Kxe6 16. cxd5+ Kd7 17. Qf3 $16) 13. O-O Bd6 (13... c6 {seems to be the only
alternative and here white can continue in two ways} 14. cxd5 $5 {This might
be a direct refutation} (14. Rb1 Bd6 (14... a5 15. b3 {with idea of Bb2}) (
14... Qh6 15. Qe2 Bd6 16. g3 Nf7 17. b4 Kc7 18. f4 $1 g4 19. c5 Be7 20. Nb3 $16
{Dziedzina,M (2256)-Bishop,N (2202) Lechenicher SchachServer 2009}) 15. b4 $36
{white has the initiative}) 14... exd5 15. f4 gxf4 16. Ne4 $1 {just great
preparation from Nisipeanu here} dxe4 {is the only move} (16... Qg7 {this is
poor defense} 17. Bxf4 $18 Ng6 18. Nf6+ Kd8 19. Bg3 Qh6 20. Bxg6 hxg6 21. Qe5
Bc5+ 22. Kh1 Qg7 23. Rae1 Qe7 24. Qf4 Qg7 25. b4 Bb6 26. Qd6+ Bd7 27. Nxd7 {
1-0 (27) Nisipeanu,L (2665)-Perske,T (2277) Bad Wiessee GER 2014}) 17. Bxf4
Bc5+ 18. Kh1 Bd6 19. Rad1 Rf8 20. Qxh7+ Ke8 21. Qh5+ Qf7 (21... Kd7 22. Rf2 $1
$16 {with the threat of Rxd6}) 22. Qxf7+ Nxf7 23. Bxd6 Nxd6 24. Rxf8+ Kxf8 25.
Rxd6 $14) 14. b4 $1 Ng6 {In my game Naumkin took the pawn on b4 which is
exactly what white wants} (14... Bxb4 15. cxd5 exd5 16. Bb2 $3 $40 Bd6 $2 (
16... Bxd2 {is better but black's position looks grim anyway} 17. Rad1 Qf7 18.
Qe2 Bf4 19. Rxd5+ Qxd5 20. Rd1 Qxd1+ 21. Qxd1+ $16) 17. f4 $1 {is winning
immediately} ({I played} 17. Rae1 Re8 18. f4 gxf4 19. Kh1 b6 20. Nf3 $18 {
Castellanos,R (2491)-Naumkin,I (2471)/Cesenatico (FC) ITA 2012}) 17... gxf4 (
17... Nf3+ 18. Nxf3 Qxb2 19. Qxg5 Qxc2 20. Qg7+ $18) 18. Rae1 Nf3+ 19. Nxf3
Qxb2 20. Qxd5 $18 {black can't defend. For example} c6 21. Qf7+ Kd8 22. Rd1 Qb4
23. Rfe1 Bd7 24. Ne5 Be8 25. Qg7 $18 Rf8 26. Nc4) 15. Rb1 {this is good enough}
({probably better is} 15. Nb3 Nf4 16. Bxf4 Qxf4 17. g3 Qf6 18. f4 gxf4 19. c5
Qe5 (19... Be7 20. Rxf4 Qc3 21. Raf1 $16 Qxc2 $2 22. Nd4 Qg6 23. Qe5 $18) 20.
Qh3 Be7 21. Rae1 Qg5 22. Nd4 Kd8 23. c6 bxc6 24. Nxc6+ Ke8 25. Re5 Qg7 26. Ba4
Kf7 27. Rxf4+ Bf6 28. Re1 h5 29. Rxf6+ Kxf6 30. Qh4+ Kg6 31. Bc2+ Kh6 32. Re5 {
1-0 (32) Mista,A (2599)-Puranik,A (2479) Warsaw POL 2017}) 15... Nf4 16. Qd1
Qh6 (16... Rf8 $5 17. c5 Be7 (17... Be5 18. g3) 18. g3 Nh3+ 19. Kg2 Qh6 (19...
Nxf2 20. Qe2 $16) 20. Nc4 $16) 17. g3 Qh3 $2 {Losing immediately} (17... Nh3+
18. Kg2 Rf8 19. Nf3 dxc4 20. Be4 Qg7 21. Nd2 c3 22. Kxh3 cxd2 23. Qxd2 e5 24.
Kg2 $16) 18. gxf4 Bxf4 19. Nf3 g4 20. Qd4 gxf3 21. Qg7+ Kc6 22. b5+ Kb6 23. c5+
Kxc5 24. Ba3+ Kb6 25. Qd4+ {1-0 (19) Babaev,R (2488)-Barria Zuniga,D (2427)
Collado Villalba 2007 EXT 2008} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
