[White "1.e4 e5 2.d4 d5 3.Nd2 dxe4"]
[Black "4.Nxe4 Nf6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C10"]
[Annotator "IM Renier Castellanos"]
[PlyCount "63"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 {This is a rare move compared to 4...
Bd7 or 4...Nd7 but still a playable option. I should be inferior but of course,
black already knows that and yet he is willing to give a fight so we must be
prepared.} 5. Nxf6+ gxf6 {This is the best.} (5... Qxf6 {is the ''safe
option'' but after thhe following setup white obtains a good game. For example:
} 6. Nf3 {Threatens Bg5 with a very awkward attack against the black queen} h6
7. Bd3 Nc6 8. O-O Bd6 9. c3 $1 {This is a very precise move, not that can't
play other moves for example 9.Re1 but 9.c3 keeps some options open that may
be useful as we shall see.} O-O ({is too early for} 9... e5 $2 10. Nxe5 Nxe5
11. dxe5 Bxe5 12. f4 Bd6 13. Re1+ Kd8 14. Qf3 Re8 15. Be3 $16 {Van Perlo,
G-Boyd,F Netherlands 1982}) (9... Bd7 10. Re1 O-O-O 11. b4 $1 $16 {white's
attack is quite fast. For example} g5 12. b5 Ne7 {Colovic,A (2404)-Galego,L 
(2496) Campillos 2005 and now} 13. a4 $1 {looks very promising for white. The
idea is just a5-Nd2-Ne4 I would call it winning attack} (13. Nd2 $5)) 10. Bc2
$5 {is a good option} e5 {fails to} (10... Re8 11. Nd2 $1 {this is a key idea}
e5 12. Ne4 Qh4 13. Nxd6 cxd6 14. Qd3 f5 15. Bd2 $14 {I settle for this
position here with the bishop pair, if black now plays} (15. Be3 $14) 15...
exd4 16. Rae1 $1 {with the initiative}) 11. Qd3 g6 12. d5 (12. Bxh6 Re8 13.
Rfe1 Bf5 14. Qd2 Bxc2 15. Qxc2 exd4 16. Bg5 Qh8 17. h3 $14 {should be an edge
as well}) 12... Bf5 13. Qe2 e4 14. Nd2 Qe5 15. g3 Qxd5 16. Nxe4 Kg7 17. Nxd6
Bxc2 18. Qxc2 cxd6 19. c4 Qh5 20. Qd1 $14) 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Bf4 $5 {This move
prevents the plan with Qd6-Bd7-000 but it is not clear that is the best. Just
one more way to go but I like it} ({I could also advise starting a flexible
plan with} 7. c3 Qd6 8. Be3 Bd7 9. Nd2 f5 (9... O-O-O 10. Ne4 Qe7 11. Qa4 {
I presume white is better here}) 10. g3 Qd5 11. Rg1 (11. Nf3 {is possible})
11... O-O-O 12. Bg2 Qb5 13. Qc2 {with the idea of queenside castle and I like
white's position very much.}) 7... e5 {The only critical try} (7... Bg7 8. c3
O-O 9. Bd3 $14) 8. Be3 $1 (8. dxe5 {is a mistake} Qe7 $1 {and black is totally
fine}) 8... Bg4 (8... Be6 9. c3 Qd7 10. Qa4 {and white is either castling
queenside next or playing Bb5 with good pressure}) 9. Bb5 $6 {perhaps not the
best} (9. Be2 Rg8 (9... Qd6 10. c3 O-O-O 11. Qa4 {looks better for white}) 10.
c3 Qd5 11. dxe5 Qxd1+ 12. Rxd1 fxe5 13. g3 $14) 9... Qd6 $6 (9... Qd5 {is
critical} 10. c4 Qe4 11. h3 Bh5 12. dxe5 Rd8 $1 13. Qe2 Bb4+ 14. Kf1 fxe5 {
hard to believe white has any advantage here at all, if anything.}) 10. c3 e4
$6 (10... Qd5 11. Be2 $1 Rg8 12. dxe5 Qxd1+ 13. Rxd1 fxe5 14. g3 $14) 11. h3
exf3 $2 {After this white obtains a clear advantage because of his powerful
bishop pair and superior structure.} (11... Be6 12. Nd2 f5 13. g3 $14 {white
has the better structure} (13. g4 $5)) 12. hxg4 fxg2 13. Rg1 a6 14. Bd3 $1 Ne7
15. Qf3 (15. Rxg2 $16) 15... O-O-O 16. Rxg2 Nd5 17. Be4 Kb8 18. Bd2 {Caruana
rightly keeps his asset.} Nb6 {In a bad position Rapport gambles everything to
a Caruana mistake that he never got. The game is over} 19. Bxb7 Nc4 20. Bf4 Qb6
21. Be4 Re8 22. Kf1 $1 h5 23. gxh5 Bh6 24. b3 Nd2+ 25. Bxd2 Bxd2 26. Rd1 Bg5
27. Bc6 Re6 28. d5 Re5 29. Rg4 a5 30. Ra4 Qc5 31. Rdd4 Rg8 32. Qd3 {1-0 (32)
Caruana,F (2782)-Rapport,R (2691) Wijk aan Zee NED 2014} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
