[White "1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nd2 dxe4"]
[Black "The Rubinstein Variation"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C07"]
[Annotator "IM Renier Castellanos"]
[PlyCount "171"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 {This system has always been popular
so it needs to be taken seriously. There are many ways for white to play
against the Rubinstein variation but none of them guarantee a clear advantage.
Here I propose a less popular way of playing which was recently tried by GM
Nepomniatchi against the Rubinstein specialist GM Meier.} 5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Nxf6+
Nxf6 7. g3 $5 {This looks like a great plan at first sight. White wants to put
the bishop on the long diagonal where it exerts pressure on black's queenside.}
b6 {This is black's main move. Some alternatives are:} (7... c5 8. Bg2 cxd4 9.
Qxd4 $1 {we go into the endgame confidently that our bishops pointing at the
queenside will give us a strong pressure.} Qxd4 10. Nxd4 Bc5 $6 {this just
helps white} (10... a6 11. Bd2 $5 Bc5 12. Nb3 Bb6 13. Ba5 $1 $14) 11. Nb3 Bd6
12. Be3 O-O 13. O-O-O Bc7 14. Bc5 Re8 15. Rhe1 h6 16. Nd2 Nd7 17. Ba3 Nf6 18.
Nc4 a5 19. Nd6 Bxd6 20. Bxd6 $16 {Reinderman,D (2584)-Brandenburg,D (2511)
Dieren NED 2015}) (7... Be7 {is too passive} 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O c5 10. dxc5 Bxc5
11. Qe2 Qc7 12. Ne5 Nd7 13. Nc4 (13. Bf4 $5) 13... Nb6 14. Bf4 Qe7 {Kovacevic,
A (2557)-Konjicanin,M (2286) Sarajevo 2013} 15. Nxb6 $5 (15. Ne5 $14 Nd5 16.
Bd2) 15... Bxb6 (15... axb6 16. a3 $16) 16. Rad1 Bc7 17. Be3 {I believe white
has enough pressure here}) 8. Bb5+ $1 {a turn of the events} ({black seems to
be doing OK after} 8. Bg2 {although I must say, the positions look very
playable and there is everything to play for.} Bb7 9. O-O Bd6 10. Qe2 O-O 11.
Rd1 h6 (11... Qc8 12. Bg5 (12. c4 $5) 12... Ne4 13. Be3 Nf6 {Nakamura,H (2741)
-Grachev,B (2654) Moscow 2010 and now} 14. c4 {followed by Rac1 looks like a
small advantage for white}) 12. c4 Qe7 13. Ne5 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Bxe5 15. Qxe5 Rfd8
16. Qe2 Rd7 17. Be3 Rad8 18. Qf3 Ne8 19. b3 Nd6 $5 (19... Qf6 {would have kept
the game level}) 20. d5 $1 Nf5 21. Re1 Qf6 22. dxe6 fxe6 23. Bf4 Nh4+ 24. gxh4
Rf8 25. Rad1 Rxd1 $2 (25... Rdf7 26. Re4 e5 27. Rde1 exf4 28. h5 $11) 26. Rxd1
Qxf4 27. Qxf4 Rxf4 28. Kg3 Rf5 29. Rd8+ Kh7 30. Rd7 $16 {white went on to win
Harikrishna,P (2698)-Giri,A (2720) Wijk aan Zee NED 2013}) 8... Bd7 9. a4 a6 (
9... Bxb5 10. axb5 $14 {cannot be recommended} Qd5 11. Qe2 Bd6 12. O-O O-O 13.
b3 $14) 10. Be2 Bc6 11. O-O Be7 {We need to also be aware of 11...Bd6} (11...
Bd6 12. Ne5 Bxe5 {this is the main line} (12... Bd5 {Robson, R (2628)-Nyzhnyk,
I (2613) Saint Louis USA 2014} 13. c4 Be4 (13... Bb7 14. Bf3 $16 {white takes
the c6 square here}) 14. a5 O-O 15. Bg5 {it seems to me that black is under
some pressure}) 13. dxe5 Qxd1 (13... Qd5 14. Qxd5 Nxd5 15. a5 $1 b5 16. Bd2
O-O-O 17. Rfd1 Rd7 18. f3 Ne7 (18... Rhd8 19. Kf2 Ne7 20. Bg5 Rxd1 {Morozevich,
A (2694)-Pelletier,Y (2590) Biel 2011} 21. Bxd1 $1 {Keeping one rook looks
best. It's a more pleasant endgame for white, although I'm certain that black
can hold with best play.}) 19. Bb4 Rhd8 20. Bxe7 Rxe7 21. Kf2 Red7 22. Ke3 Bd5
23. b3 c5 24. f4 Kc7 25. g4 g6 26. h4 Bc6 27. Rxd7+ Rxd7 28. Bd3 Kd8 29. h5 $14
{This is the endgame that black needs to suffer. In Zhigalko, S (2658)-Stupak,
K (2515) Minsk BLR 2012 black managed to draw but it is not pleasant to play.})
14. Rxd1 Nd7 15. Ra3 $1 Bb7 (15... Nxe5 16. Bf4 $16) 16. a5 b5 17. f4 O-O-O 18.
Be3 Nb8 19. Rc1 $1 $16 {The D file is useless with the two white bishops
controlling the key entry squares. White wants to open the position with c4.
This is a game of correspondence chess and it is quite instructive} h5 20. b4
h4 21. g4 Nc6 22. c4 bxc4 23. Rxc4 Rd7 24. Kf2 Rhd8 25. b5 $1 axb5 26. Rc5 b4
27. Ra4 Rd5 28. a6 Ba8 29. Rc1 Ra5 30. Rxa5 Nxa5 31. a7 Rd7 32. Ra1 Nb7 (32...
Nc6 33. Ba6+ Kd8 34. Bb7 $1 {kills}) 33. Bb5 Rd5 34. Bc6 Rd3 35. Ke2 Rc3 36.
Rc1 Ra3 37. Rd1 Ra2+ 38. Kf1 Ra5 39. Bf2 Nc5 40. Bxa8 Rxa7 41. Bh1 Ra5 42. Bxh4
Nb7 43. Bc6 Ra3 44. Be7 Rc3 45. Bd7+ Kb8 46. Bxb4 Rf3+ 47. Ke2 Rxf4 48. Rb1
Rxg4 49. Be7 Re4+ 50. Kd3 Rxe5 51. Bc6 {1-0 (51) LePage,C (2409)-Groth,D (2302)
ICCF 2014}) 12. Ne5 Bb7 13. c4 Nd7 14. Bf3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Nxe5 16. dxe5 O-O 17.
Rd1 Qe8 18. Be3 Bb4 19. h4 $14 {The position is only slightly in white's favor.
} h6 20. Rd4 (20. Rd3 $5 Rd8 21. Rxd8 Qxd8 22. Qc6 (22. Rd1 Qe8 23. b3 Qc8 {
followed by Rd8. Even here black is passive but should hold}) 22... a5 23. Rc1
$14) 20... Bc5 (20... Qe7 {followed by Rad8 seems best} 21. Rad1 Rad8 22. Qc6
Rxd4 23. Rxd4 Qc5 $1 $11) 21. Rg4 Bxe3 22. Qxe3 Kh8 23. c5 $14 Qc6 24. cxb6
Qxb6 25. Qc3 Rfd8 26. Rc4 Rd7 27. Rc1 Rb8 28. b4 Kg8 29. h5 {I'm not sure this
move is necessary right now but it makes sense to fix the kingside} Qb7 30. Kh2
Qd5 31. Qe3 Qd2 32. Qxd2 Rxd2 33. Rf4 Rb7 34. Kg2 Rd5 35. Rc6 Rxe5 36. Rxa6
Rxh5 37. b5 g6 38. Ra8+ (38. Rc6 Rd5 39. Kf3 Kg7 40. Ke3 $16) 38... Kg7 39. Re8
c6 $1 $11 {The endgame is now equal as black manages to activate his rook} 40.
bxc6 Rc7 41. Rc4 Kf6 (41... Ra5 $1 {was the right defense} 42. Rb8 Raa7 $1 {
defending against Rb7} 43. Kf3 Kf6 {followed by Ke7-Kd6 white can't make
progress}) 42. Ra8 Ke7 43. a5 Kd6 44. Rd8+ Ke7 45. Ra8 Kd6 46. Ra4 Kxc6 47. a6
Kb6 48. Rb4+ Kc6 49. a7 Ra5 50. Rc4+ Kb7 51. Rxc7+ Kxa8 52. Rxf7 $16 {If black
can save or not this endgame I can't tell for sure. Certainly it is difficult
so I'll leave the rest without comment. My philosophy is that this game plan
looks pretty grim for black, he is fighting to equalize and white plays for
two results without any risks. I'll take that.} h5 53. Rh7 Rxa7 54. Rh8+ Kb7
55. Rh6 Kc6 56. Rxg6 Kd6 57. Kh3 $1 Ra1 58. Rh6 Ke7 59. Rxh5 Kf6 60. Rh6+ Kf7
61. Kh4 Re1 62. Kg4 Kg7 63. Rh5 Kg6 64. f4 Rg1 65. Re5 Kf6 66. Kf3 Rf1+ 67. Kg2
Ra1 68. g4 Ra3 69. Kf2 Ra1 70. Re3 Rb1 71. Kf3 Rb5 72. Kg3 Ra5 73. Rb3 Ra1 74.
g5+ Kf5 75. Rb5+ Kg6 76. Re5 Kf7 77. Re3 Ra4 78. Kf3 Rb4 79. Ra3 Rc4 80. Ra7+
Kf8 81. g6 Rc1 82. Kg4 Rg1+ 83. Kh5 Kg8 84. Kh6 Rh1+ 85. Kg5 Rf1 86. Re7 {
1-0 (86) Nepomniachtchi, I (2733)-Meier, G (2655) Hersonissos GRE 2017} *

