[Black "The Fort Knox Variation"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C07"]
[Annotator "IM Renier Castellanos"]
[PlyCount "131"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bd7 $5 {This move is also seen often in
tournament practice. It is a solid choice and difficult to break. The arising
positions resemble the Caro Kan defense} 5. Nf3 Bc6 6. Bd3 Nd7 7. O-O Ngf6 8.
Ng3 $1 {It is important to avoid the massive simplification of pieces in the
center. If white wants to play for a win it's better to keep more pieces on
the board} (8. Ned2 {is another possibility}) 8... Be7 (8... g6 $5 {is popular
nowadays thanks to Jobava's games mostly. White should continue now with} 9. b3
$1 {this wins an important tempo} Bg7 10. Ba3 Bf8 11. Bb2 Bg7 12. c4 O-O 13.
Re1 (13. Qe2 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 c6 15. Rfe1 Qa5 16. a3 Rfd8 17. Rad1 Rac8 18. b4 Qc7
19. Bc1 $5 e5 20. Bg5 $5 {Navara,D (2735)-Kunin,V (2595) Gjakova KOS 2016} (20.
Bf1 $14)) 13... a5 (13... b6 $5) (13... Bxf3 14. Qxf3 c6 {is similar to the
mentioned game of Navara but white is up a tempo}) 14. a3 b6 15. Qe2 Bb7 16.
Rad1 {Simple chess, white is slightly better Cheparinov, I (2700)-Tratar,M 
(2498) Legnica POL 2013}) 9. Re1 O-O {Here are two setups for white, one he
can play with c4 and the other he can play with the pawn on c3. We need to
know both as black can force us into going in the system he prefers} 10. c3
Bxf3 {Black shows he does not mind playing against the c3 setup. However, I
have concluded that after 10...Bd5 white should play 11.c4 and assume the
setup with the pawns more advanced and slightly weaker} (10... Bd5 $5 11. c4
Bxf3 12. Qxf3 c6 13. Bf4 {Others prefer developing with b3-Bb2. I like the way
Korneev plays with the bishop on f4 taking the c7 square away from the black
queen.} (13. Be3 {is possible as well.}) 13... Re8 (13... Qb6 14. Red1 Qxb2
$140 15. Rab1 Qxa2 16. Rxb7 $44 {white should be better here because of more
active pieces}) 14. Rad1 {Once we have arranged our pieces in the center, our
plan is to attack black's kingside by advancing the H pawn. For example:} Qb6 (
14... Nf8 15. h4 $1 {Typical plan for white} Bd6 $6 (15... Qb6 16. Ne2 $1 Qxb2
$6 17. Rb1 $16) 16. Bg5 N8d7 17. Bb1 h6 $6 {this weakens the position of the
king now white can retreat his bishop and try to exploit this weakness later}
18. Bd2 a5 {threatening to trade the bishops with Bb4} 19. a3 $1 Nf8 20. Bc3
$16 {1-0 (31) Jenni,F-Priehoda,V/Leipzig 2002}) 15. Re2 {white defends b2
without weakening the queenside. If white plays b3 then a5 gives black
counterplay so it's better to not advance any pawns} Nf8 16. Be3 Qc7 17. h4 $1
{Again we see this typical idea} Rad8 18. h5 h6 19. Bf4 Qb6 20. Be3 Qc7 21. a3
{White is only a little better. He can think of advancing his queenside pawns
and combine play in both wings. Let's go over the game a bit further} a5 $6 22.
Bf4 Qc8 23. Red2 a4 24. Ne2 $1 {Just going to c3 with a nice space advantage}
Qa8 25. Bc7 Rc8 26. Be5 N6d7 27. Bf4 Qa5 28. Nc3 $16 {Korneev, O-Hillarp
Persson, T Barcelona 2004}) 11. Qxf3 c6 12. Bf4 {This is the best square for
the bishop in my opinion} Re8 (12... Nd5 13. Bd2 Re8 14. a3 Nf8 15. c4 Nf6 16.
Bc3 Qc7 17. Rad1 $16 {Di Tomaso,O-Varela,G/Buenos Aires CAA op 1993 White has
a very nice setup here}) (12... Qb6 13. Rab1 c5 14. dxc5 Bxc5 $14 {White is
better with his nice pair of bishops and queenside majority}) 13. Rad1 Nf8 14.
a3 $5 Ng6 (14... Nd5 15. Bc1 b5 16. Ne4 Nd7 17. g3 $1 {preparing h4} N7f6 18.
h4 Rc8 19. Bc2 {I would say white is clearly better here}) 15. Bc1 Qc7 16. Ne4
Nxe4 17. Bxe4 Rad8 18. g3 Rd7 19. h4 Nf8 20. Bf4 $16 {The opening has been a
great success for white} Qd8 (20... Bd6 21. Be3) 21. b4 $5 Bd6 22. Be3 a6 23.
c4 f5 $6 {this move weakens severely black's structure} (23... Qc7 24. c5 $5
Be7 25. Rd2 {The plan is: defend the d4 pawn and then advance a4-b5}) 24. Bc2
Rf7 25. Bg5 Qb8 26. Bc1 Qd8 27. Bg5 $1 Qb8 28. Kg2 h6 29. Bc1 Qd8 30. Rh1 $1
Qf6 31. Bb2 Bb8 32. Bc3 Kh8 33. Rde1 Nd7 34. Re2 e5 35. dxe5 Bxe5 (35... Nxe5
36. Qf4 $18 {wins}) 36. Rhe1 Ree7 37. Bxe5 Rxe5 38. Rxe5 Nxe5 39. Qf4 Ng6 40.
Re8+ Kh7 41. Qf3 Nf8 42. h5 (42. c5 {was also very strong} Ne6 43. Bxf5+ Qxf5
44. Qxf5+ Rxf5 45. Rxe6 {should be a winning endgame}) 42... g6 43. hxg6+ Nxg6
44. Qe3 Kg7 45. Re6 Qg5 46. Qd4+ Kh7 47. f4 Qg4 48. Bd1 $18 Nh4+ $8 49. Kf2 Qh3
50. gxh4 Rg7 51. Bf3 Qxh4+ 52. Ke2 Qh2+ 53. Kd3 Qa2 54. Qd6 Qxa3+ 55. Ke2 Qa2+
56. Ke3 Qh2 57. Be2 $1 c5 58. bxc5 a5 59. Qe5 Qh3+ 60. Kd2 a4 61. Bd3 Rg2+ 62.
Kc3 a3 63. Qf6 Rg7 64. Kb4 Qxd3 65. Qxh6+ Kg8 66. Re8+ {1-0 (66) Leko,
P-Seirawan,Y Istanbul 2000} *

[Event "?"]
