[White "3...c5 Problems for white"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C07"]
[Annotator "IM Renier Castellanos"]
[PlyCount "43"]
[EventDate "2018.??.??"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. dxc5 Nf6 6. Ngf3 Qxc5 7. Bd3 Nbd7
8. O-O Qc7 $1 {This is possibly black's most precise move order and for some
reason it went uncovered in the first edition of the repertoire database. This
was recommended by Jacob Aagard and Nikolaos Ntirlis in the book Playing The
French from 2013. Black's idea is to play Nc5 on the next move} (8... Be7 {
is analyzed the previous edition}) 9. a4 $5 {The first edition repertoire
database of 3.Nd2 was based on Michael Adam's choices so let's choose this as
the main path to follow} (9. Nb3 Bd6 $1 {There are only 3 games with this move
in my database and it seems like this move is a tough one to crack. The bishop
is much more active on d6 than on e7 and enables black to play Bf4 at some
point which could be useful. Also, the slight pressure on h2 may force white
to make a concession.} (9... Be7 10. a4 {is again a transposition to the lines
previously analyzed in the first edition}) (9... g6 $5 $146 {It's hard to see
novelties at such an early stage of the game these days but here is one
interesting move by Andrew Greet. Fortifying the kingside makes sense.} 10. a4
{white follows the usual path gaining some space on the queenside.} Bg7 11. Re1
O-O 12. a5 Nd5 $1 13. c3 Rd8 14. Bg5 N7f6 15. Qd2 $14 {with natural moves
white has obtained a comfortable position. Certainly, Greet's 9...g6 seems
interesting to me and it leads to fighting positions but as things stand now
white looks better to me.}) 10. Qe2 (10. a4 {Robson,R (2645)-Arjun,U (1779)
Columbus USA 2017} O-O $5 (10... b6 {is also possible when} 11. a5 Bb7 12. axb6
axb6 13. Rxa8+ Bxa8 14. Nbd4 Qb8 15. Nb5 Bc5 16. Qe2 O-O {is satisfactory for
black}) 11. a5 e5 12. Re1 Re8 {the threat of e4 is unpleasant} 13. Nfd2 (13.
Nbd2 Nc5 $1 $15) 13... e4 14. Nxe4 Bxh2+ 15. Kh1 Nxe4 16. Rxe4 Rxe4 17. Bxe4
Nf6 18. Bf3 Be6 {followed by Rd8 black seems fine}) 10... O-O 11. Bg5 b6 (11...
Bf4 12. Rfe1 b6 13. Rad1 Bb7 $11 {Kulkarni,R (2296)-Sundararajan,K (2456)
Paris FRA 2016}) 12. Rad1 {this is definitely harmless as we will see} Bb7 13.
Nbd4 (13. h3 {is no improvement. Black obtains a good game either with} a6 $1 {
I like black very much here. Basically, we don't have any targets as white} (
13... h6 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15. Ba6 Bd5 $11)) 13... a6 14. Rfe1 Rfe8 15. Bc4 b5 16.
Bb3 Ne4 17. c3 (17. Bh4 Ndc5 $15) 17... Bxh2+ 18. Nxh2 Nxg5 19. Bc2 Nf6 20. Ng4
Nge4 $17 {Bruedigam,M (2408)-Bluebaum,M (2642) Berlin GER 2017}) (9. Qe2 Nc5
10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Bxd7+ Ncxd7 12. c4 $11 {leads to balanced positions. I
believe this is a playable option for both sides, white has a queenside
majority that could be of some use in the endgame but black has no weaknesses}
Be7 13. b3 O-O 14. Bb2 Rfd8 $11) 9... Nc5 10. Bc4 (10. Bb5+ {has been played a
few times with no special results for white}) 10... Be7 11. a5 O-O 12. Qe2 Bd7
(12... b6 $5 {is also possible here} 13. a6 (13. axb6 Qxb6 14. Nb3 Nxb3 15.
Bxb3 a5 {white can't really put much pressure on black's queenside, in fact,
it is black who could take over the initiative}) 13... Bd7 14. Nd4 Rac8 15. Nb5
Qb8 16. b3 (16. c3 Rfd8 17. Nf3 Nce4 18. Bd3 Nc5 19. Bc2 h6) 16... Bxb5 (16...
Rfd8 $5) 17. Bxb5 Nd5 18. Bb2 {Tiviakov,S (2583)-Kuipers,S (2440) Groningen
NED 2017 and now} Qf4 $1 {with the idea of Bf6 next would have been at least
equal for black}) 13. Ne5 Be8 14. Re1 Ncd7 (14... Bd6 $5 15. h3 Rc8 16. Ndf3 a6
{looks solid for black} 17. c3 h6 18. Bd2 Ncd7 $11) 15. Ndf3 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Nd7
17. Bf4 Nxe5 18. Bxe5 Bd6 19. Bd3 Bxe5 20. Qxe5 Qxe5 21. Rxe5 Bc6 22. f4 $14 {
Adams, M (2744)-Lupulescu, C (2631) Reykjavik ISL 2015 The endgame is
unpleasant for black although he eventually held the draw. It seems like this
is a reasonable try for white, however with just a little precise play black
can equalize. Not to mention that 12...b6! is a good alternative for black.} *

