1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. dxc5 Nf6 6. Ngf3 Qxc5 7. Bd3 Nbd7 {
In view of what is exposed on the previous note, it's probably time to find
new ways for white to handle this line. A recent game of Gawain Jones shows an
interesting path:} 8. Qe2 $5 {white's idea is to hide the bishop quickly on c2
when Nc5 comes} Qc7 9. c3 $5 {before going down this road let us have a look
at some alternatives} (9. Nb3 {without having committed to kingside castle
this move gives us more options than before. For instance} Bd6 (9... Be7 $1 10.
Bg5 b6 11. O-O-O {risky} (11. Bh4 $11) 11... O-O 12. Kb1 Bb7 13. Rhe1 Rfe8 ({if
} 13... a6 {then} 14. Nfd4 Rfe8 {just transposes}) 14. Nfd4 a6 15. g3 b5 16. h4
Bf8 17. c3 Bd5 (17... h6 $5 18. Bc1 b4 $1 {black has the initiative}) 18. g4
Nc5 $6 19. Nxc5 Bxc5 20. Bxf6 gxf6 21. Bc2 $16 {left white with a clear
advantage although the game was eventually a draw. Adams, M (2753)-Schenk, A 
(2489) Germany 2014}) 10. Nbd4 {now threatens Nb5 and Nf5}) (9. c4 {was played
by Lawerence Trent} Be7 10. O-O b6 11. b3 Bb7 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Ne4 {White plays
in Catalan style trying to make something out of his queenside majority} (13.
Rad1 Rfd8 {does not change things}) 13... Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Bxe4 15. Qxe4 Bf6 16.
Bxf6 Nxf6 17. Qe5 Qb7 18. Rad1 Rfd8 19. Rd4 Rd7 20. Rfd1 Rad8 $11 {black
didn't have much problems to maintain the balance. Trent,L (2458)-Roberson,P 
(2388) Newport Pagnell ENG 2016}) (9. a4 Nc5 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Ne5 {played by
Kovalenko} a6 $1 (11... Rc8 {is also good}) 12. Nxd7 Nfxd7 13. Bc4 Qc6 $1 14.
Qf3 Qxf3 15. gxf3 (15. Nxf3 Nb6 $15) 15... Nb6 16. a5 Nd5 $1 17. Be2 Bd6 18.
Nc4 Bc7 19. Be3 Nxe3 20. fxe3 O-O-O {black was totally fine here too.
Kovalenko,I (2659)-Martinovic,S (2551) Karlsruhe GER 2017}) 9... Be7 (9... Bd6
{Bluebaum's move makes less sense here since white can play Ne4 or Nc4}) 10.
O-O b6 11. Ne4 O-O (11... Bb7 12. Bg5 {should transpose to the game}) 12. Bg5
Bb7 13. Bh4 $1 {White seeks to improve the bishop to the h2-b8 diagonal It is
hard to name advantages but I think this is a decent position to play. I
believe both sides are happy here, black has solved his opening problems and
white has avoided direct play and simplifications, this leaves plenty of room
for ideas.} Qf4 {Black must have a few good alternatives here but I don't
think white's play would be influenced greatly} (13... Rfd8 14. Rad1 {
shouldn't make much difference}) (13... Nd5 $5 {is the most direct move but
white can answer with} 14. Bg3 Nf4 15. Qe3 e5 16. Nxe5 Nxd3 17. Nxd3 Qc6 18. f3
{white is half a pawn up}) 14. Bg5 Qc7 15. Rad1 Rfd8 (15... Rfe8 {is
definitely a solid option} 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. Bb5 Red8 18. Rxd7 Rxd7 19. Bxf6
gxf6 20. Bxd7 Qxd7 21. Rd1 Qc7 {Ducarmon,Q (2488)-Peralta,F (2582) Sitges ESP
2014 and was a draw in the end}) 16. Rfe1 Rac8 17. Bh4 Qf4 $6 {Maybe it was
better to trade everything on e4 although white can claim a minimal edge} (
17... Bxe4 18. Bxe4 Nxe4 19. Bxe7 Re8 20. Ba3 (20. Bh4 $5)) 18. Bg3 Qg4 19.
Nxf6+ (19. Neg5 {was tempting with the idea of h3. Black should play} Rc5 $1 (
19... Bxf3 20. Nxf3 Nh5 21. Qc2 $1 Nxg3 (21... g6 $2 22. h3 $18) 22. Bxh7+ Kh8
23. hxg3 g6 24. Rxd7 Rxd7 25. Ne5 Qf5 26. Qxf5 gxf5 27. Nxd7 Kxh7 28. Ne5 $14)
20. Qe3 $1 {with the idea of Be2} Qh5 21. Be2 Ng4 22. Qf4 Bxg5 23. Nxg5 Qxg5 (
23... Rxg5 $2 24. Rxd7 $18) 24. Qxg4 Qxg4 25. Bxg4 $14 {white must be better})
19... Bxf6 20. Ba6 $1 $16 {Black is in real trouble now} Bxa6 (20... Nc5 {
is the same} 21. Rxd8+ Rxd8 22. Bxb7 Nxb7 23. Qa6 Nc5 24. Qxa7) 21. Qxa6 Nc5
22. Rxd8+ Rxd8 23. Qxa7 Nd3 24. h3 Qc4 25. Rd1 h5 26. Qxb6 Qxa2 27. Ne5 $1 Qxb2
28. Qc7 Rf8 29. Nd7 Qe2 30. Ra1 Qb2 (30... Re8 {was better} 31. Nxf6+ gxf6 32.
Qd7 Rf8 33. Qd4 Kg7 34. Bh4 {with a winning position} e5 35. Qd6 $18) 31. Ra7
Bd8 32. Qd6 Qb1+ 33. Kh2 Re8 34. Qc6 (34. Ra8 $18) 34... h4 35. Nf6+ Bxf6 36.
Qxe8+ Kh7 37. Qxf7 hxg3+ 38. fxg3 Qb8 39. Qxf6 Qxa7 40. Qh4+ Kg8 41. Qd8+ Kf7
42. Qxd3 Qc5 43. h4 e5 44. g4 g6 45. Qf3+ Kg7 46. g5 Qc4 47. Qb7+ Kg8 48. Qb4
Qd5 49. Qb8+ Kf7 50. Qa7+ Ke6 51. Qa6+ Kf5 52. Kg3 Qd1 53. Qf6+ Ke4 54. Qf3+
Qxf3+ 55. gxf3+ {1-0 (55) Jones,G (2640)-Adhiban,B (2655) Wijk aan Zee NED
2018 Jones shows a different way for white to play which is still fresh and
although black seems to be able to equalize at least there isn't as much
forced variations as in the other lines mentioned in Game 1 of this update.} *

