1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nf6 {This line was not
covered in the first edition of the database so it needed to be added. It is
not a dangerous line but it is played from time to time and white must know a
few things to play for a win.} 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 8. O-O Be7 9. dxc5
Nxc5 {In this line black should always be just slightly worse but the
simplified nature of the position makes it difficult for white to actually get
something tangible, on the other hand, we can say the risk for white is also
very small. White has a few setups he can try here and I don't think any is
better than other. I present here some ideas for you to choose:} 10. Nb3 (10.
Nd4 {this is a direct approach, the idea is Nf5} Qd7 (10... O-O {is also
possible and now} 11. Nf5 Re8 12. Nb3 Ne6 13. Nxe7+ Qxe7 14. Be3 a6 15. Re1
Rad8 16. c3 Qc7 17. f3 Nh5 18. Qd2 g6 19. Nd4 Nhg7 20. Bf2 Nxd4 21. Qxd4 Qc4
22. Qb6 Qc6 23. Qb4 $14 {Sokolov,A (2605)-Short,N (2650) Linares 1989}) 11.
N2f3 O-O 12. Bf4 Rfe8 13. Re1 Nce4 (13... Bf8 14. Ne5 Qa4 15. c3 Qa6 16. Qe2
Qxe2 17. Rxe2 Bd6 18. Nd7 $1 Bxf4 19. Rxe8+ Rxe8 20. Nxc5 {white has a
symbolical advantage that eventually Karpov converted into a full point:
Karpov,A (2740)-Bareev,E (2685) Linares 1994}) 14. Ne5 Qd8 15. Nd3 Rc8 16. c3
Bf8 17. Qb3 Nh5 (17... Qd7 18. f3 Nc5 19. Qc2 Nxd3 20. Qxd3 $14) 18. Bg3 (18.
Qxb7 $5 Nxf4 19. Nxf4 Rb8 20. Qxd5 Qxd5 21. Nxd5 Rxb2 22. f3 Nd6 23. Rxe8 Nxe8
24. Re1 Nd6 25. Re2 $14) 18... Nhxg3 19. hxg3 Qd7 20. Rad1 {Adams,M (2615)
-Short,N (2660) England 1991 I suspect black should be OK but white's position
is slightly easier to play.}) (10. Re1 {With this move we want Nf1 followed by
Be3-Bd4} O-O 11. Nf1 Re8 12. Be3 a5 $1 {Probably the best} (12... Nce4 13. c3
Qc7 14. Bd4 Bc5 15. Ne3 Rad8 16. Qd3 Qb6 17. Re2 Bxd4 18. Nxd4 Nc5 19. Qc2 Qa6
20. a3 $14 {Adams,M (2742)-Pelletier,Y (2549) France 2002}) 13. a4 (13. c3 b5 (
13... a4 14. a3 Qa5 15. Qc2 Rad8 16. Rad1 Nfe4 17. Ng3 Nxg3 18. hxg3 g6 19. Bd4
Ne6 20. Be5 $14 {Quesada Perez,Y (2493)-Sambuev,B (2562) Havana 2014}) 14. Bd4
b4 15. Ne3 Nce4 16. c4 dxc4 17. Nxc4 Rc8 {black has equalized}) 13... Rc8 14.
c3 Qb6 15. Re2 Qb3 16. Qxb3 Nxb3 17. Rae1 Bc5 18. N1d2 {1/2-1/2 (18) Vachier
Lagrave,M (2573)-Rozentalis,E (2582) France 2007}) 10... Nce4 (10... O-O {
doesn't bring any significant change to the position. White could follow with}
11. Nxc5 (11. Be3 $5) 11... Bxc5 12. Bg5 Rc8 13. c3 Rc6 {Tal,M (2625)-Benko,P 
(2515) Skopje 1972 and now I like} 14. Qd3 {with idea of Rfe1 and Rad1} Rb6 $6
15. Bxf6 Rxf6 16. Rad1 $14) 11. Nfd4 Qd7 12. f3 $5 {Perhaps the most promising
line for white} (12. Qf3 {is also good} O-O 13. Nf5 Bd8 14. Be3 {Typical in
this line our bishop will be great on d4} Rc8 15. c3 Re8 16. Bd4 a6 {this was
played in Navara,D (2565)-Baklan,V (2605) Bled (ol) 2002 to me it looks like
white is slightly better.} 17. Rad1 $146 Rc6 18. Ne3 Bc7 19. g3 Rce6 20. Bxf6
Rxf6 21. Qg4 Qxg4 22. Nxg4 Rd6 23. Ne3 Nf6 24. Kg2 g6 25. Rd3 $14) 12... Nd6
13. Nc5 {In this line white is able to keep more pieces on the board} Qc8 {
this is more precise} (13... Qc7 14. Nd3 O-O 15. b3 {Note how the pawns on b3
and f3 are essential to keep the black knights out of play} (15. c3 {with the
idea of Re1-bf4 should also be safe enough for a slight edge}) (15. Kh1 $5 Rfe8
16. b3 Rad8 17. Be3 g6 18. Qd2 a6 19. Rae1 Nb5 20. Nxb5 axb5 21. Bd4 $14 {
Wei Yi (2649)-Liu,C (2368) Jiangmen CHN 2014}) 15... Rfe8 16. Be3 Rac8 17. Re1
Bf8 (17... Qa5 18. Bf2 $14) 18. Qd2 h6 19. Kh1 a6 20. a4 $14 {Xiong,J (2660)
-Vorontsov,P (2463) Dallas USA 2016}) 14. Nd3 O-O 15. Bf4 (15. b3 Bd8 $1 {
the point of 13...Qc8}) 15... Re8 16. Re1 Nf5 17. Nxf5 Qxf5 18. Qd2 Rac8 19.
Rad1 $14 {with the idea of Be5 next and c3} *

