1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nc6 $5 {The ever-popular Guimard variation. In the
first edition of the database repertoire, I recommended the sharp 6.Bd3. That
seems like a fine choice however here I present a more strategic line which
perhaps is even more promising.} 4. Ngf3 Nf6 5. e5 Nd7 6. Be2 {here we will
analyze 6...f6 and 6...Be7} f6 (6... Be7 7. O-O (7. Nf1 $5) 7... O-O 8. Re1 f6
9. exf6 Bxf6 10. c3 {white is planning Bd3-Nf1-Ne3-Ng4 and black's only plan
is to achieve e6-e5 so he must try right now} e5 11. Qb3 $1 Nb6 (11... exd4 12.
Qxd5+ Kh8 13. Ne4 {gives white a powerful initiative.} (13. Nxd4 {is also good}
) 13... dxc3 14. bxc3 Nb6 15. Qb3 Bf5 16. Nxf6 Qxf6 17. Bb2 {followed by c4 is
one way to play it}) 12. a4 $1 {this is stronger than the inmediate 12.Nxe5} a5
13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Nf3 Bd6 (15... Bf6 16. Be3 $16 {black has
problems to defend d5. Rad1 next and Bxb6 is an idea}) (15... Bf4 {is probably
best} 16. Bxf4 Rxf4 17. Bd3 Bg4 18. Ne5 Qg5 19. h4 Qh5 20. g3 Rf6 {Tabatabaei,
M (2509)-Ganjali,H (2214) Tehran IRI 2017} 21. f4 $16 (21. Be4 $5 {with the
idea of Bg2-Nd3 is good})) 16. Bg5 $1 Be7 (16... Qe8 17. Be3 {wins a pawn with
dubious compensation for black}) 17. Be3 (17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Bd3 Qf6 19. Be4 $14
{is possible. It is uncomfortable for black to defend d5 for instance} Be6 $2
20. Bxh7+ Kxh7 21. Rxe6 $18) 17... Kh8 (17... c5 18. Bd3 Bd6 19. Ng5 h6 20. Ne4
$16) 18. Bxb6 cxb6 19. Nd4 Bd6 20. Bf3 $16 {was excellent for white Van
Foreest,J (2616)-Haria,R (2364) Tarvisio ITA 2017}) 7. exf6 Qxf6 8. Nf1 $1 {
It is very important to put the pressure on d5 before black can play e6-e5 in
good conditions} Bd6 ({If black plays} 8... e5 9. Ne3 $1 Nb6 (9... Nxd4 10.
Nxd4 exd4 11. Nxd5 Qe5 12. c4 {The position is already winning for white} c6
13. Bf4 Qf5 14. Nc7+ Kd8 15. O-O Nc5 16. Qxd4+ Bd7 17. Rad1 Rc8 18. b4 Na6 19.
Nxa6 bxa6 20. Bg5+ {1-0 (20) Venevtsev,A (2140)-Beliaev,V (2063) Lipetsk 2007})
(9... exd4 10. Nxd5 {followed by Bc4 +-}) (9... e4 10. Nxd5 Qd6 11. Bc4 $1 exf3
12. O-O {this has been played a couple of times but can't be recommended.
White's attack is decisive for example} Qg6 13. Nxc7+ Kd8 14. Ne6+ Ke8 15. Ng5
Nd8 16. Qxf3 Nb6 17. Re1+ Be7 18. Bb5+ Bd7 19. Bxd7+ Nxd7 20. d5 $18 {
Todorovic,G (2475)-Brkljaca,A (2353) Belgrade 2007}) 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Nxd5 {
with a healthy extra pawn}) 9. Ne3 O-O 10. O-O {There are many games in this
position. The strategy for white is to make e6-e5 as much difficult as
possible for black by playing in the center. Sometimes with Ne3-Ng4 other
times by creating central tension with c4} Qg6 {the most popular move} (10...
Nb6 {is also seen often and now} 11. Ng4 {white could also insert the moves 11.
a4 a5 and only then 12.Ng4} Qg6 12. h3 e5 13. Ngxe5 Bxe5 (13... Nxe5 14. Nxe5
$1 (14. dxe5 Bc5 {could be some compensation}) 14... Bxe5 15. Bh5 Qd6 16. dxe5
Qxe5 17. Re1 Qd6 18. Bg5 Be6 19. Qe2 $16 {the two bishops and activity give
white a good advantage}) 14. dxe5 $1 Bxh3 15. Nh4 (15. Ng5 {is also strong} Bc8
(15... Bf5 $2 16. Bh5 Qh6 17. g4 {is winning} Bc8 18. f4 $18) 16. f4 Ne7 17.
Bd3 Bf5 18. g4 Bxd3 19. Qxd3 Qxd3 20. cxd3 $16 {I prefer white}) 15... Qe4 16.
f4 Bd7 17. Bd3 Qd4+ 18. Kh1 g6 19. c3 Qc5 20. Qe1 $16 {Dolmatov,S (2495)
-Yurtaev,L Sochi 1978}) (10... Ne7 11. Bd3 {with the ideas of Ng4-Re1-h3}) (
10... b6 {is not that bad} 11. c3 Qg6 12. Bd3 Qh5 13. Re1 Nf6 14. Nf1 $14) 11.
c4 $1 {White's idea now is to play c5 driving the bishop away from the
dangerous diagonal and also gain full control over the e5 square} Nf6 12. c5
Be7 13. Bb5 Bd7 (13... Nd7 {has scored well in practice and here I propose a
different approach} 14. Kh1 $5 a6 (14... Rxf3 15. gxf3 $16) 15. Ba4 Qh5 16. Re1
Nf6 17. Nf1 Ne4 18. Be3 {and white is ready to play Ng3 next}) 14. b4 {I think
this is the most promising} (14. a4 a5 $13 (14... Qe8 15. Bxc6 Bxc6 16. b4 $14)
) 14... a5 (14... Nxb4 15. Ne5 Qe8 16. Nxd7 Nxd7 17. Rb1 a5 18. a3 Nc6 19. Ba4
Rb8 20. Ng4 $44) (14... Qe8 15. Bxc6 Bxc6 16. a4 a6 17. Ne5 Nd7 18. N3g4 h5 19.
Nxd7 Bxd7 20. Ne5 $14 {Hill,A (2257)-Puranik,A (2469) Abu Dhabi UAE 2016}) 15.
Bd3 Qe8 16. b5 Nb4 17. a4 Nxd3 18. Qxd3 Qh5 19. Ne5 Rad8 20. Ba3 $16 {Mocchi,T
(2223)-Stella,A (2433) Condino 2014} *

